{"title_page": "Jonathan Ashworth", "text_new": "{{Other people||John Ashworth (disambiguation){{!}}John Ashworth}}\n{{short description|british Labour and Co-operative politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jonathan Ashworth\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Jonathan Ashworth MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Ashworth in 2020\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]<ref>Shadow Secretary of State for Health (2016\u20132020). [[Barbara Keeley]] held the brief of [[Social care in England]] until [[Sir Keir Starmer]] appointed Ashworth with the additional responsibilities of social care. </ref>\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br />[[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor = [[Diane Abbott]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister without portfolio|Shadow Minister without Portfolio]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 14 September 2015\n| term_end1 = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor1 = [[Jon Trickett]]\n| successor1 = [[Andrew Gwynne]]\n| office2 = [[Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Chairman of the National Executive Committee]]\n| leader2 = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 11 July 2013\n| term_end2 = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor2 = ''Position abolished''\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]\n| term_start3 = 5 May 2011\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[Peter Soulsby]]\n| successor3 = \n| majority3 = 22,675 (45.2%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|10|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Salford]], England\n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Emilie Oldknow|3 July 2010}}\n| children = 2\n| alma_mater = [[Durham University]]\n| website = {{Official website}}\n}}\n'''Jonathan Michael Graham Ashworth''' (born 14 October 1978) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician serving as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]] since 2011, and has served as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]] in the [[Shadow Cabinet]]s of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and [[Keir Starmer]] since 2016. Ashworth was first elected at a [[2011 Leicester South by-election|by-election in 2011]], following the resignation of his predecessor [[Peter Soulsby]], and was re-elected at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]] general elections.\n\nHe previously worked as an adviser to [[Gordon Brown]] and head of party relations for [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=\"Mercury profile\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Ashworth-pledges-champion-city/article-3352055-detail/article.html |title=Labour candidate Ashworth promises to be a 'champion' for city if he wins by-election |newspaper=[[Leicester Mercury]] |first=Adrian |last=Troughton |date=21 March 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423180253/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Ashworth-pledges-champion-city/article-3352055-detail/article.html |archivedate=23 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe served Shadow Health Secretary, shadowing [[Matt Hancock]] alongside the Shadow Social Care Minister [[Barbara Keeley]], <ref>{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/shadow-cabinet/|title=Shadow Cabinet|website=The Labour Party|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/Opposition/Cabinet|title=Her Majesty's Official Opposition: The Shadow Cabinet|website=UK Parliament|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> having been appointed to the role by party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in October 2016. In April 2020, Ashworth was reappointed to the position by new Labour Leader [[Sir Keir Starmer]], gaining the additional portfolio of [[Social care in England]].\n\n==Education==\nAshworth was born in [[Salford]], brought up in north [[Manchester]] and educated at [[Philips High School]] in Bury and [[Bury College]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U254664 |chapter=Ashworth, Jonathan Michael Graham |title=Who's Who 2012 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2012 |edition=online |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref> before studying politics and philosophy at the [[University of Durham]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet and ministerial appointments following the June 2017 general election |publisher=NHS Providers|date=6 July 2017|page=10|url=https://nhsproviders.org/media/3274/updated-cabinet-and-ministerial-appointments-following-the-june-2017-general-election-july-2017.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jonashworth.org/about-jon- |title=Your Strong Voice for Leicester South: Jon Ashworth: Standing to be your new MP |work=Jonashworth.org |accessdate=7 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308214917/http://www.jonashworth.org/about-jon- |archivedate=8 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2000 he served as National Secretary of [[Labour Students]].<ref name=\"Team Brown\">{{cite news |title=Bright young things beavering away for Team Brown |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Labour Party officer===\nAshworth began working for the Labour Party as a Political Research Officer in 2001, and was the Economics and Welfare Policy Officer from 2002 to 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/27620.stm |title=Jon Ashworth MP |work=BBC Democracy Live |accessdate=30 May 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305203011/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/27620.stm |archivedate=5 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2003, he was seconded to the [[Scottish Labour Party]] to work on the [[2003 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament election campaign]], where he worked closely with then-[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Gordon Brown]].  Following the election, Scottish Labour remained the single-largest party at Holyrood and were re-elected, but the coalition with the Scottish Lib Dems remained in place.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Special adviser===\nFrom 2004, he was appointed as [[Special advisers (UK government)|Special Adviser]] to [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury|Chief Secretaries to the Treasury]] [[Paul Boateng]], [[Des Browne]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Times guide to the Government |newspaper=[[The Times]] |location= London |date=13 May 2005}}</ref> and [[Stephen Timms]], but in practice he worked for [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] Gordon Brown. His main job was liaising with the Labour movement and an ''[[Evening Standard]]'' profile said \"his contact book was \"stuffed with constituency officers and union organisers\", and there was newspaper speculation that he would be Political Secretary at [[10 Downing Street]] in a potential future [[Brown government]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Gordon gets his team prepared to take over No 10 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=6 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nWhen Gordon Brown became Prime Minister in June 2007, Ashworth was appointed deputy Political Secretary with the role of linking the Government to the trade unions.<ref name=\"Team Brown\" /> There was speculation later that year that Ashworth might be selected to replace [[John Prescott]] as the official Labour candidate for [[Kingston upon Hull East (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Hull East]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Who's in the running to succeed Prescott? |newspaper=[[Hull Daily Mail]] |date=22 August 2007}}</ref> although it came to nothing. Ashworth spent most of the [[2008 Crewe and Nantwich by-election|Crewe and Nantwich by-election]] campaign in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gaby |last=Hinsliff |title=Labour in Turmoil: Is this the beginning of the end for Brown? |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |location= London |date=25 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Labour Party were defeated at the 2010 general election, Ashworth became Political Secretary to the acting party leader [[Harriet Harman]]. He did not publicly support any candidate in the subsequent leadership election because of his role working for [[Harriet Harman]] but he was described as a \"key member\" of [[Ed Miliband]]'s team on the day after Miliband won the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Francis |last1=Elliott |first2=Chris |last2=Smyth |title=Dallas and demand management: what really does it for Ed |newspaper=The Times |location= London |date=27 September 2010}}</ref> When Miliband was elected as Leader of the Labour Party, he asked Ashworth to join his office as Head of Party Relations.<ref name=\"Mercury profile\" />\n\n===Parliamentary candidate===\nWith a general election imminent, Ashworth was identified as someone who the Labour Party leadership wished to find a seat for. He was linked with a possible candidature in [[Mansfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Mansfield]] should the sitting [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) [[Alan Meale]] decide to stand down, but Meale decided to seek re-election despite widespread speculation he was to retire from Parliament. Ashworth was then identified as a potential candidate for [[Nottingham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham East]] when the sitting MP [[John Heppell]] retired,<ref>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Walker |title=MP calls it a day after a royal time |newspaper=[[Nottingham Evening Post]] |date=3 April 2010}}</ref> but the selection went to former MP [[Chris Leslie (politician)|Chris Leslie]] when the Labour [[National Executive Committee]] chose to impose Leslie at the last minute.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Brady |title=Activists threaten rebellion as Brown helps secure seat for ally |newspaper=[[Independent on Sunday]] |location= London |date=11 April 2010 |page=10}}</ref>\n\nAshworth sought selection in [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]] in 2011 when the sitting MP [[Peter Soulsby]] decided to resign to seek election as [[Mayor of Leicester]]. He was immediately identified as the front-runner for the selection and was backed by the major trade unions including his own [[Unite the Union|Unite]], [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] and [[UNISON]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAshworth was also endorsed by the [[Co-Operative Party]] and is also a [[Co-Operative Party]] MP.<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour is to reveal MP candidates |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=17 March 2011}}</ref> He was selected on the first ballot by the local party, and held the seat with an increased majority on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adrian |last=Troughton |title=Great day for Labour capped by victory in by-election |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Labour Party parliamentary candidate selections===\nFollowing the row over alleged undue influence of [[Trade unions in the United Kingdom|trade unions]] in the [[Labour Party in the Falkirk Parliamentary Selection in 2013]], Ashworth penned a piece for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' claiming that it is ordinary people \u2013 not the unions \u2013 who choose Labour MPs.<ref name=jon>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/10159801/Labours-links-to-the-trade-unions-Im-proud-of-them.html |title=Labour's links to the trade unions? I'm proud of them |first=Jon |last=Ashworth |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=4 July 2013 |accessdate=8 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707111558/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/10159801/Labours-links-to-the-trade-unions-Im-proud-of-them.html |archivedate=7 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2013, Ashworth replaced [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] on the [[National Executive Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://labourlist.org/2013/07/jonathan-ashworth-to-replace-tom-watson-on-labours-nec/ |first=Mark |last=Ferguson |title=Jonathan Ashworth to replace Tom Watson on Labour's NEC |date=11 July 2013 |website=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223841/http://labourlist.org/2013/07/jonathan-ashworth-to-replace-tom-watson-on-labours-nec/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Labour Opposition (2015\u2013)===\n[[File:Official portrait of Jonathan Ashworth crop 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Ashworth in 2017]]\n\nAshworth nominated [[Yvette Cooper]] to be [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Leader of the Labour Party]] following the resignation of [[Ed Miliband]] after the 2015 general election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-backs-Yvette-Cooper-city-neighbour/story-26662467-detail/story.html |title=Jon Ashworth backs Yvette Cooper over city neighbour Liz Kendall in Labour leadership race |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=9 June 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917070434/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-backs-Yvette-Cooper-city-neighbour/story-26662467-detail/story.html |archivedate=17 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He nominated [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] as Deputy Leader.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-deputy-leadership-election |title= Who nominated who in the 2015 Labour deputy leadership election? |work= [[New Statesman]] |location= London |accessdate= 24 June 2016 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151225083138/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-deputy-leadership-election |archivedate= 25 December 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his election as Labour Party leader, [[Jeremy Corbyn]] appointed Ashworth to the [[Shadow Cabinet]] role of Shadow Minister without Portfolio.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-South-MP-Jon-Ashworth-Jeremy-Corbyn-s/story-27794193-detail/story.html |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Leicester South MP Jon Ashworth becomes Jeremy Corbyn's shadow minister without portfolio |date=14 September 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925082348/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-South-MP-Jon-Ashworth-Jeremy-Corbyn-s/story-27794193-detail/story.html |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ashworth was appointed Shadow Secretary of State for Health in October 2016. He has gone on record to say that a Labour government would not repeal the controversial Health and Social Care Act 2012 despite Labour's 2017 general election manifesto commitment to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthcaretimes.co.uk/labour-will-not-roll-back-health-and-social-care-act/|title=Labour Will not Roll Back Health and Social Care Act \u2013 Healthcare Times|website=healthcaretimes.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001165609/https://healthcaretimes.co.uk/labour-will-not-roll-back-health-and-social-care-act/|archivedate=1 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Ashworth voted against the resolution to authorise [[United Kingdom and ISIL|RAF bombing of ISIL in Syria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-MP-Leicester-Leicestershire-vote/story-28291270-detail/story.html |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Jon Ashworth the only MP from Leicester and Leicestershire to vote against Syria air strikes |date=3 December 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225165452/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-MP-Leicester-Leicestershire-vote/story-28291270-detail/story.html |archivedate=25 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] campaign a recording of a conversation Ashworth had with a [[Conservatism|Conservative]] activist friend was leaked to the media, where Ashworth said he did not believe Labour would win the election due to Corbyn and the [[Brexit]] position not appealing to voters. Ashworth subsequently apologised to the Labour Party, stating he was just \"joshing around\".<ref name=bbc-20191210>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50726592 |title=General election 2019: Jonathan Ashworth apologises after Corbyn criticism leak |work=BBC News |date=10 December 2019 |access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAshworth supported [[Lisa Nandy]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/here-are-the-23-mps-backing-wigan-s-lisa-nandy-in-the-labour-party-leadership-contest-1-10193818|title=Here are the 23 MPs backing Wigan's Lisa Nandy in the Labour Party leadership contest|website=www.wigantoday.net|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> When [[Keir Starmer]] won the contest, he decided to keep Ashworth on as the Shadow Secretary of State for Health, extending his portfolio to include social care.\n\n==Views==\nAshworth is critical of problems in the [[National Health Service|NHS]]. Ashworth stated, \"The 4.3 million patients on waiting lists and the nearly 27,000 patients who waited over 62 days for cancer treatment last year will feel sorely let down that reducing waiting lists and stamping out rationing isn\u2019t the first priority of the new health secretary. Investment in technology is welcome but years of Tory [[United Kingdom government austerity programme#Effects|austerity]] has seen hospitals build up a \u00a35,000,000,000 repair backlog, resulting in clinicians nationwide using hundreds of pieces of equipment that are years out of date, as recently revealed by Labour. And commitments to prevention will ring hollow without reversing the substantial cuts to public health budgets, which are set to reach \u00a3800,000,000 by 2020/21.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jul/20/nhs-to-receive-487m-technology-boost-matt-hancock|title=NHS to receive \u00a3487m technology boost|last=Siddique|first=Haroon|date=20 July 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720083058/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jul/20/nhs-to-receive-487m-technology-boost-matt-hancock |archivedate=20 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-44895002|title=Low NHS morale is 'heartbreaking' says Matt Hancock|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720013215/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-44895002|date=20 July 2018|archivedate=20 July 2018|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nAshworth is also concerned about closure of maternity units, Ashworth stated, \"Expectant mothers deserve reassurance that the local maternity unit will be there for them when needed. It is a disgrace that almost half of maternity units in England had to close to new mothers at some point in 2017. The uncertainty for so many women just when they need the NHS most is unthinkable.  Under this government, maternity units are understaffed and under pressure. Labour is committed to making child health an absolute priority with our ambition of the healthiest children in the world. That means giving every child the best start in life, including proper investment in maternity services.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/28/nhs-maternity-unit-closures-labour-midwives|title=NHS maternity units were forced to close 287 times last year|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=28 August 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828134819/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/28/nhs-maternity-unit-closures-labour-midwives|archivedate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAshworth fears cuts to public health services are causing cancellations of children's operations.  Ashworth stated, \"Behind each of these cancellations is a sick child and their loved ones facing unnecessary distress for entirely avoidable reasons.  These cancelled operations risk harming children further in the long term and it\u2019s shameful that cancellations have reached this level [18647 children's operations cancelled in 2017].  The fact that thousands of children\u2019s operations \u2013 including for broken bones, removing rotten teeth, eye surgery and even breast cancer \u2013 have had to be cancelled on this scale reveals yet again an NHS pushed to the brink by the Tories.\u201d<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/27/record-number-of-childrens-operations-cancelled-last-year Record number of children's operations cancelled last year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027191122/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/27/record-number-of-childrens-operations-cancelled-last-year |date=27 October 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAshworth expressed concern over staff shortages in the NHS, projected to increase during the coming decade.  Ashworth maintains this is due to government mismanagement and financial restrictions on the NHS since 2010.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/15/nhs-could-be-short-of-350000-staff-by-2030 NHS \u2018could be short of 350,000 staff by 2030\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115080721/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/15/nhs-could-be-short-of-350000-staff-by-2030 |date=15 November 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAshworth maintained the NHS needed extra support from the government to prevent a crisis in the winter 2018/2019.  Ashworth stated, \"There was no extra cash for acute trusts in the recent budget for winter and we know many hospitals are facing intense pressures following this year\u2019s \u2018summer crisis\u2019.  It would be unforgivable if patients suffer another winter like last year.  [winter 2017/2018 when many patients spent hours in ambulances or on hospital trolleys because there was no room in wards] Ministers urgently need to reassure us they have a plan and will make proper funds available.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/26/doctors-worried-hospital-cope-winter-royal-college-physicians Most doctors fear hospitals won't cope this winter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126141756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/26/doctors-worried-hospital-cope-winter-royal-college-physicians |date=26 November 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nIn December 2018 Ashworth was concerned about winter hospital provision and feared the government is unable to deal with the NHS due to pressure over [[Brexit]].  Ashworth stated, \"This is a government dismally paralysed by the ongoing Tory civil war over the Brexit shambles. It will be an utterly embarrassing failure of leadership if the health secretary can\u2019t get an NHS plan published because of the ongoing squabbling.  A&Es are already overcrowded at unsafe levels this winter, waiting lists are getting longer and staff shortages across the NHS becoming more chronic. We need urgent action now.  If the government can\u2019t even get its proposals for the NHS agreed internally, then it should stand aside for a Labour government that will put patients first over this debilitating Tory civil war.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/dec/14/brexit-forces-nhs-leaders-to-delay-their-long-term-plan Long-term plan for NHS funding delayed amid Brexit chaos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215040350/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/dec/14/brexit-forces-nhs-leaders-to-delay-their-long-term-plan |date=15 December 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nIn November 2019 Ashworth expressed concern that staff shortages in the NHS lead to staff doing unpaid overtime to care for patients.  Ashworth said, \"The NHS is in crisis after nearly a decade of Tory cuts and it\u2019s a disgrace that its dedicated staff, who always put their patients first, are having to pick up the pieces to fill the gaps left by this crisis made in Downing Street.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/nov/15/nhs-staff-working-1m-hours-a-week-of-unpaid-overtime-labour-says NHS staff working 1m hours a week of unpaid overtime, Labour says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116100009/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/nov/15/nhs-staff-working-1m-hours-a-week-of-unpaid-overtime-labour-says |date=16 November 2019 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nDuring the year to December 2019 4,668 patient deaths were linked to safety incidents at hospital, mental health and ambulance trusts.  Ashworth said, \"These figures are heartbreaking and our thoughts are with the families who have lost a loved one in these circumstances.\" He held, \"years of Tory  cutbacks\" responsible for understaffing and for increasing pressures, which put patients at risk.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/dec/08/deaths-of-4600-nhs-patients-linked-to-safety-incidents-says-labour Deaths of 4,600 NHS patients linked to safety incidents] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209151918/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/dec/08/deaths-of-4600-nhs-patients-linked-to-safety-incidents-says-labour |date=9 December 2019 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2019, it emerged that Ashworth had told a friend that he did not believe Labour would win the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] due to be held two days later. He said that this was largely due to the unpopularity of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and voters outside the cities blaming Labour for not delivering Brexit. His friend, who was a Conservative activist, leaked a recording of the conversation to [[Guido Fawkes (website)|Guido Fawkes]]. Ashworth later claimed that he was joking.\n\n==Personal life==\nAshworth became engaged to Emilie Oldknow, the East Midlands Regional Director for the Labour Party, in 2008. She was the official Labour candidate for [[Sherwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Sherwood]] at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], but was not elected.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Parsons |title=Farmer Mark in a thriller at dawn |newspaper=Nottingham Evening Post |date=8 May 2010}}</ref> Former [[UK Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] and his wife [[Sarah Jane Brown|Sarah]] attended the couple's wedding on 3 July 2010 in [[Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Guest Appearance |newspaper=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |location= London |date=4 July 2010}}</ref> They have a daughter, Gracie, born in May 2011 shortly after his by-election victory,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/oh-baby-joy-city-s-new-mp-gracie-born/story-12107473-detail/story.html |title=Oh baby! Joy for city's new MP as Gracie born |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=23 May 2011 |accessdate=24 June 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and a second daughter, Annie.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.jonashworth.org|Jon Ashworth MP}}\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = jonathan-ashworth/4244 | hansard = | hansardcurr = <!-- 5971 --> | guardian = 14333/jonathan-ashworth | publicwhip = Jonathan_Ashworth | theywork = 25120/jon_ashworth/leicester_south | record = | bbc = 27620.stm | journalisted = jon-ashworth }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Soulsby]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]|years=[[2011 Leicester South by-election|2011]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Chair of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Trickett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister without portfolio|Shadow Minister without Portfolio]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Gwynne]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Diane Abbott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{British special advisers}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{East Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashworth, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Aidan's College, Durham]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Shadow Secretaries of State for Health]]\n[[Category:People from Salford]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Leicestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people||John Ashworth (disambiguation){{!}}John Ashworth}}\n{{short description|british Labour and Co-operative politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jonathan Ashworth\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Jonathan Ashworth MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Ashworth in 2020\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]<ref>Shadow Secretary of State for Health (2016\u20132020). [[Barbara Keeley]] held the brief of [[Social care in England]] until [[Sir Keir Starmer]] appointed Ashworth with the additional responsibilities of social care. </ref>\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br />[[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor = [[Diane Abbott]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister without portfolio|Shadow Minister without Portfolio]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 14 September 2015\n| term_end1 = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor1 = [[Jon Trickett]]\n| successor1 = [[Andrew Gwynne]]\n| office2 = [[Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Chairman of the National Executive Committee]]\n| leader2 = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 11 July 2013\n| term_end2 = 7 October 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor2 = ''Position abolished''\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]\n| term_start3 = 5 May 2011\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[Peter Soulsby]]\n| successor3 = \n| majority3 = 22,675 (45.2%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|10|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Salford]], England\n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Emilie Oldknow|3 July 2010}}\n| children = 2\n| alma_mater = [[Durham University]]\n| website = {{Official website}}\n}}\n'''Jonathan Michael Graham Ashworth''' (born 14 October 1978) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician serving as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]] since 2011, and has served as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]] in the [[Shadow Cabinet]]s of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and [[Keir Starmer]] since 2016. Ashworth was first elected at a [[2011 Leicester South by-election|by-election in 2011]], following the resignation of his predecessor [[Peter Soulsby]], and was re-elected at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]] general elections.\n\nHe previously worked as an adviser to [[Gordon Brown]] and head of party relations for [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=\"Mercury profile\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Ashworth-pledges-champion-city/article-3352055-detail/article.html |title=Labour candidate Ashworth promises to be a 'champion' for city if he wins by-election |newspaper=[[Leicester Mercury]] |first=Adrian |last=Troughton |date=21 March 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423180253/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Ashworth-pledges-champion-city/article-3352055-detail/article.html |archivedate=23 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe served Shadow Health Secretary, shadowing [[Matt Hancock]] alongside the Shadow Social Care Minister [[Barbara Keeley]], <ref>{{cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/shadow-cabinet/|title=Shadow Cabinet|website=The Labour Party|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/Opposition/Cabinet|title=Her Majesty's Official Opposition: The Shadow Cabinet|website=UK Parliament|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> having been appointed to the role by party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in October 2016. In April 2020, Ashworth was reappointed to the position by new Labour Leader [[Sir Keir Starmer]], gaining the additional portfolio of [[Social care in England]].\n\n==Education==\nAshworth was born in [[Salford]], brought up in north [[Manchester]] and educated at [[Philips High School]] in Bury and [[Bury College]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U254664 |chapter=Ashworth, Jonathan Michael Graham |title=Who's Who 2012 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2012 |edition=online |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref> before studying politics and philosophy at the [[University of Durham]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet and ministerial appointments following the June 2017 general election |publisher=NHS Providers|date=6 July 2017|page=10|url=https://nhsproviders.org/media/3274/updated-cabinet-and-ministerial-appointments-following-the-june-2017-general-election-july-2017.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jonashworth.org/about-jon- |title=Your Strong Voice for Leicester South: Jon Ashworth: Standing to be your new MP |work=Jonashworth.org |accessdate=7 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308214917/http://www.jonashworth.org/about-jon- |archivedate=8 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2000 he served as National Secretary of [[Labour Students]].<ref name=\"Team Brown\">{{cite news |title=Bright young things beavering away for Team Brown |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Labour Party officer===\nAshworth began working for the Labour Party as a Political Research Officer in 2001, and was the Economics and Welfare Policy Officer from 2002 to 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/27620.stm |title=Jon Ashworth MP |work=BBC Democracy Live |accessdate=30 May 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305203011/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/27620.stm |archivedate=5 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2003, he was seconded to the [[Scottish Labour Party]] to work on the [[2003 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament election campaign]], where he worked closely with then-[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Gordon Brown]].  Following the election, Scottish Labour remained the single-largest party at Holyrood and were re-elected, but the coalition with the Scottish Lib Dems remained in place.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Special adviser===\nFrom 2004, he was appointed as [[Special advisers (UK government)|Special Adviser]] to [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury|Chief Secretaries to the Treasury]] [[Paul Boateng]], [[Des Browne]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Times guide to the Government |newspaper=[[The Times]] |location= London |date=13 May 2005}}</ref> and [[Stephen Timms]], but in practice he worked for [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] Gordon Brown. His main job was liaising with the Labour movement and an ''[[Evening Standard]]'' profile said \"his contact book was \"stuffed with constituency officers and union organisers\", and there was newspaper speculation that he would be Political Secretary at [[10 Downing Street]] in a potential future [[Brown government]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Gordon gets his team prepared to take over No 10 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=6 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nWhen Gordon Brown became Prime Minister in June 2007, Ashworth was appointed deputy Political Secretary with the role of linking the Government to the trade unions.<ref name=\"Team Brown\" /> There was speculation later that year that Ashworth might be selected to replace [[John Prescott]] as the official Labour candidate for [[Kingston upon Hull East (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Hull East]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Who's in the running to succeed Prescott? |newspaper=[[Hull Daily Mail]] |date=22 August 2007}}</ref> although it came to nothing. Ashworth spent most of the [[2008 Crewe and Nantwich by-election|Crewe and Nantwich by-election]] campaign in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gaby |last=Hinsliff |title=Labour in Turmoil: Is this the beginning of the end for Brown? |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |location= London |date=25 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Labour Party were defeated at the 2010 general election, Ashworth became Political Secretary to the acting party leader [[Harriet Harman]]. He did not publicly support any candidate in the subsequent leadership election because of his role working for [[Harriet Harman]] but he was described as a \"key member\" of [[Ed Miliband]]'s team on the day after Miliband won the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Francis |last1=Elliott |first2=Chris |last2=Smyth |title=Dallas and demand management: what really does it for Ed |newspaper=The Times |location= London |date=27 September 2010}}</ref> When Miliband was elected as Leader of the Labour Party, he asked Ashworth to join his office as Head of Party Relations.<ref name=\"Mercury profile\" />\n\n===Parliamentary candidate===\nWith a general election imminent, Ashworth was identified as someone who the Labour Party leadership wished to find a seat for. He was linked with a possible candidature in [[Mansfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Mansfield]] should the sitting [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) [[Alan Meale]] decide to stand down, but Meale decided to seek re-election despite widespread speculation he was to retire from Parliament. Ashworth was then identified as a potential candidate for [[Nottingham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham East]] when the sitting MP [[John Heppell]] retired,<ref>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Walker |title=MP calls it a day after a royal time |newspaper=[[Nottingham Evening Post]] |date=3 April 2010}}</ref> but the selection went to former MP [[Chris Leslie (politician)|Chris Leslie]] when the Labour [[National Executive Committee]] chose to impose Leslie at the last minute.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Brady |title=Activists threaten rebellion as Brown helps secure seat for ally |newspaper=[[Independent on Sunday]] |location= London |date=11 April 2010 |page=10}}</ref>\n\nAshworth sought selection in [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]] in 2011 when the sitting MP [[Peter Soulsby]] decided to resign to seek election as [[Mayor of Leicester]]. He was immediately identified as the front-runner for the selection and was backed by the major trade unions including his own [[Unite the Union|Unite]], [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] and [[UNISON]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAshworth was also endorsed by the [[Co-Operative Party]] and is also a [[Co-Operative Party]] MP.<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour is to reveal MP candidates |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=17 March 2011}}</ref> He was selected on the first ballot by the local party, and held the seat with an increased majority on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adrian |last=Troughton |title=Great day for Labour capped by victory in by-election |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Labour Party parliamentary candidate selections===\nFollowing the row over alleged undue influence of [[Trade unions in the United Kingdom|trade unions]] in the [[Labour Party in the Falkirk Parliamentary Selection in 2013]], Ashworth penned a piece for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' claiming that it is ordinary people \u2013 not the unions \u2013 who choose Labour MPs.<ref name=jon>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/10159801/Labours-links-to-the-trade-unions-Im-proud-of-them.html |title=Labour's links to the trade unions? I'm proud of them |first=Jon |last=Ashworth |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=4 July 2013 |accessdate=8 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707111558/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/10159801/Labours-links-to-the-trade-unions-Im-proud-of-them.html |archivedate=7 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2013, Ashworth replaced [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] on the [[National Executive Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://labourlist.org/2013/07/jonathan-ashworth-to-replace-tom-watson-on-labours-nec/ |first=Mark |last=Ferguson |title=Jonathan Ashworth to replace Tom Watson on Labour's NEC |date=11 July 2013 |website=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223841/http://labourlist.org/2013/07/jonathan-ashworth-to-replace-tom-watson-on-labours-nec/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Labour Opposition (2015\u2013)===\n[[File:Official portrait of Jonathan Ashworth crop 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Ashworth in 2017]]\n\nAshworth nominated [[Yvette Cooper]] to be [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Leader of the Labour Party]] following the resignation of [[Ed Miliband]] after the 2015 general election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-backs-Yvette-Cooper-city-neighbour/story-26662467-detail/story.html |title=Jon Ashworth backs Yvette Cooper over city neighbour Liz Kendall in Labour leadership race |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=9 June 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917070434/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-backs-Yvette-Cooper-city-neighbour/story-26662467-detail/story.html |archivedate=17 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He nominated [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] as Deputy Leader.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-deputy-leadership-election |title= Who nominated who in the 2015 Labour deputy leadership election? |work= [[New Statesman]] |location= London |accessdate= 24 June 2016 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151225083138/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-deputy-leadership-election |archivedate= 25 December 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his election as Labour Party leader, [[Jeremy Corbyn]] appointed Ashworth to the [[Shadow Cabinet]] role of Shadow Minister without Portfolio.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-South-MP-Jon-Ashworth-Jeremy-Corbyn-s/story-27794193-detail/story.html |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Leicester South MP Jon Ashworth becomes Jeremy Corbyn's shadow minister without portfolio |date=14 September 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925082348/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-South-MP-Jon-Ashworth-Jeremy-Corbyn-s/story-27794193-detail/story.html |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ashworth was appointed Shadow Secretary of State for Health in October 2016. He has gone on record to say that a Labour government would not repeal the controversial Health and Social Care Act 2012 despite Labour's 2017 general election manifesto commitment to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthcaretimes.co.uk/labour-will-not-roll-back-health-and-social-care-act/|title=Labour Will not Roll Back Health and Social Care Act \u2013 Healthcare Times|website=healthcaretimes.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001165609/https://healthcaretimes.co.uk/labour-will-not-roll-back-health-and-social-care-act/|archivedate=1 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Ashworth voted against the resolution to authorise [[United Kingdom and ISIL|RAF bombing of ISIL in Syria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-MP-Leicester-Leicestershire-vote/story-28291270-detail/story.html |first=Dan |last=Martin |title=Jon Ashworth the only MP from Leicester and Leicestershire to vote against Syria air strikes |date=3 December 2015 |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |accessdate=24 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225165452/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Jon-Ashworth-MP-Leicester-Leicestershire-vote/story-28291270-detail/story.html |archivedate=25 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] campaign a recording of a conversation Ashworth had with a [[Conservatism|Conservative]] activist friend was leaked to the media, where Ashworth said he did not believe Labour would win the election due to Corbyn and the [[Brexit]] position not appealing to voters. Ashworth subsequently apologised to the Labour Party, stating he was just \"joshing around\".<ref name=bbc-20191210>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50726592 |title=General election 2019: Jonathan Ashworth apologises after Corbyn criticism leak |work=BBC News |date=10 December 2019 |access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAshworth supported [[Lisa Nandy]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/here-are-the-23-mps-backing-wigan-s-lisa-nandy-in-the-labour-party-leadership-contest-1-10193818|title=Here are the 23 MPs backing Wigan's Lisa Nandy in the Labour Party leadership contest|website=www.wigantoday.net|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> When [[Keir Starmer]] won the contest, he decided to keep Ashworth on as the Shadow Secretary of State for Health.\n\n==Views==\nAshworth is critical of problems in the [[National Health Service|NHS]]. Ashworth stated, \"The 4.3 million patients on waiting lists and the nearly 27,000 patients who waited over 62 days for cancer treatment last year will feel sorely let down that reducing waiting lists and stamping out rationing isn\u2019t the first priority of the new health secretary. Investment in technology is welcome but years of Tory [[United Kingdom government austerity programme#Effects|austerity]] has seen hospitals build up a \u00a35,000,000,000 repair backlog, resulting in clinicians nationwide using hundreds of pieces of equipment that are years out of date, as recently revealed by Labour. And commitments to prevention will ring hollow without reversing the substantial cuts to public health budgets, which are set to reach \u00a3800,000,000 by 2020/21.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jul/20/nhs-to-receive-487m-technology-boost-matt-hancock|title=NHS to receive \u00a3487m technology boost|last=Siddique|first=Haroon|date=20 July 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720083058/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jul/20/nhs-to-receive-487m-technology-boost-matt-hancock |archivedate=20 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-44895002|title=Low NHS morale is 'heartbreaking' says Matt Hancock|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720013215/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-44895002|date=20 July 2018|archivedate=20 July 2018|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nAshworth is also concerned about closure of maternity units, Ashworth stated, \"Expectant mothers deserve reassurance that the local maternity unit will be there for them when needed. It is a disgrace that almost half of maternity units in England had to close to new mothers at some point in 2017. The uncertainty for so many women just when they need the NHS most is unthinkable.  Under this government, maternity units are understaffed and under pressure. Labour is committed to making child health an absolute priority with our ambition of the healthiest children in the world. That means giving every child the best start in life, including proper investment in maternity services.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/28/nhs-maternity-unit-closures-labour-midwives|title=NHS maternity units were forced to close 287 times last year|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=28 August 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828134819/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/28/nhs-maternity-unit-closures-labour-midwives|archivedate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAshworth fears cuts to public health services are causing cancellations of children's operations.  Ashworth stated, \"Behind each of these cancellations is a sick child and their loved ones facing unnecessary distress for entirely avoidable reasons.  These cancelled operations risk harming children further in the long term and it\u2019s shameful that cancellations have reached this level [18647 children's operations cancelled in 2017].  The fact that thousands of children\u2019s operations \u2013 including for broken bones, removing rotten teeth, eye surgery and even breast cancer \u2013 have had to be cancelled on this scale reveals yet again an NHS pushed to the brink by the Tories.\u201d<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/27/record-number-of-childrens-operations-cancelled-last-year Record number of children's operations cancelled last year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027191122/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/27/record-number-of-childrens-operations-cancelled-last-year |date=27 October 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAshworth expressed concern over staff shortages in the NHS, projected to increase during the coming decade.  Ashworth maintains this is due to government mismanagement and financial restrictions on the NHS since 2010.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/15/nhs-could-be-short-of-350000-staff-by-2030 NHS \u2018could be short of 350,000 staff by 2030\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115080721/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/15/nhs-could-be-short-of-350000-staff-by-2030 |date=15 November 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nAshworth maintained the NHS needed extra support from the government to prevent a crisis in the winter 2018/2019.  Ashworth stated, \"There was no extra cash for acute trusts in the recent budget for winter and we know many hospitals are facing intense pressures following this year\u2019s \u2018summer crisis\u2019.  It would be unforgivable if patients suffer another winter like last year.  [winter 2017/2018 when many patients spent hours in ambulances or on hospital trolleys because there was no room in wards] Ministers urgently need to reassure us they have a plan and will make proper funds available.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/26/doctors-worried-hospital-cope-winter-royal-college-physicians Most doctors fear hospitals won't cope this winter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126141756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/nov/26/doctors-worried-hospital-cope-winter-royal-college-physicians |date=26 November 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nIn December 2018 Ashworth was concerned about winter hospital provision and feared the government is unable to deal with the NHS due to pressure over [[Brexit]].  Ashworth stated, \"This is a government dismally paralysed by the ongoing Tory civil war over the Brexit shambles. It will be an utterly embarrassing failure of leadership if the health secretary can\u2019t get an NHS plan published because of the ongoing squabbling.  A&Es are already overcrowded at unsafe levels this winter, waiting lists are getting longer and staff shortages across the NHS becoming more chronic. We need urgent action now.  If the government can\u2019t even get its proposals for the NHS agreed internally, then it should stand aside for a Labour government that will put patients first over this debilitating Tory civil war.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/dec/14/brexit-forces-nhs-leaders-to-delay-their-long-term-plan Long-term plan for NHS funding delayed amid Brexit chaos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215040350/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/dec/14/brexit-forces-nhs-leaders-to-delay-their-long-term-plan |date=15 December 2018 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nIn November 2019 Ashworth expressed concern that staff shortages in the NHS lead to staff doing unpaid overtime to care for patients.  Ashworth said, \"The NHS is in crisis after nearly a decade of Tory cuts and it\u2019s a disgrace that its dedicated staff, who always put their patients first, are having to pick up the pieces to fill the gaps left by this crisis made in Downing Street.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/nov/15/nhs-staff-working-1m-hours-a-week-of-unpaid-overtime-labour-says NHS staff working 1m hours a week of unpaid overtime, Labour says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116100009/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/nov/15/nhs-staff-working-1m-hours-a-week-of-unpaid-overtime-labour-says |date=16 November 2019 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nDuring the year to December 2019 4,668 patient deaths were linked to safety incidents at hospital, mental health and ambulance trusts.  Ashworth said, \"These figures are heartbreaking and our thoughts are with the families who have lost a loved one in these circumstances.\" He held, \"years of Tory  cutbacks\" responsible for understaffing and for increasing pressures, which put patients at risk.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/dec/08/deaths-of-4600-nhs-patients-linked-to-safety-incidents-says-labour Deaths of 4,600 NHS patients linked to safety incidents] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209151918/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/dec/08/deaths-of-4600-nhs-patients-linked-to-safety-incidents-says-labour |date=9 December 2019 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 2019, it emerged that Ashworth had told a friend that he did not believe Labour would win the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] due to be held two days later. He said that this was largely due to the unpopularity of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and voters outside the cities blaming Labour for not delivering Brexit. His friend, who was a Conservative activist, leaked a recording of the conversation to [[Guido Fawkes (website)|Guido Fawkes]]. Ashworth later claimed that he was joking.\n\n==Personal life==\nAshworth became engaged to Emilie Oldknow, the East Midlands Regional Director for the Labour Party, in 2008. She was the official Labour candidate for [[Sherwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Sherwood]] at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], but was not elected.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Parsons |title=Farmer Mark in a thriller at dawn |newspaper=Nottingham Evening Post |date=8 May 2010}}</ref> Former [[UK Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] and his wife [[Sarah Jane Brown|Sarah]] attended the couple's wedding on 3 July 2010 in [[Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Guest Appearance |newspaper=[[The Sunday Telegraph]] |location= London |date=4 July 2010}}</ref> They have a daughter, Gracie, born in May 2011 shortly after his by-election victory,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/oh-baby-joy-city-s-new-mp-gracie-born/story-12107473-detail/story.html |title=Oh baby! Joy for city's new MP as Gracie born |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=23 May 2011 |accessdate=24 June 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and a second daughter, Annie.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.jonashworth.org|Jon Ashworth MP}}\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = jonathan-ashworth/4244 | hansard = | hansardcurr = <!-- 5971 --> | guardian = 14333/jonathan-ashworth | publicwhip = Jonathan_Ashworth | theywork = 25120/jon_ashworth/leicester_south | record = | bbc = 27620.stm | journalisted = jon-ashworth }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Soulsby]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]|years=[[2011 Leicester South by-election|2011]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Chair of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Trickett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister without portfolio|Shadow Minister without Portfolio]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Gwynne]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Diane Abbott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{British special advisers}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{East Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashworth, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Aidan's College, Durham]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Shadow Secretaries of State for Health]]\n[[Category:People from Salford]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Leicestershire]]\n", "name_user": "JLo-Watson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLabour Opposition (2015\u2013)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Ashworth"}
{"title_page": "Brown Bears football", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| CurrentSeason    = 2019 Brown Bears football team\n| TeamName         = Brown Bears football\n| Image            = Brown Bears wordmark.png\n| ImageSize        = 100\n| HeadCoach        = [[James Perry (American football)|James Perry]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 1st\n| HCWins           = 1\n| HCLosses         = 5\n| Stadium          = [[Brown Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity     = 20,000\n| StadSurface      = [[Grass]]\n| Location         = [[Providence, Rhode Island]] \n| NCAAdivision     = I FCS\n| Conference       = [[Ivy League]]\n| FirstYear        = 1878\n| AthleticDirector = Jack Hayes\n| WebsiteName      = BrownBears.com\n| WebsiteURL       = http://brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/index\n| ATWins           = 607\n| ATLosses         = 565\n| ATTies           = 40\n| BowlWins         = 0\n| BowlLosses       = 1\n| BowlTies         = \n| NatlTitles       =\n| ConfTitles       = 4\n| DivTitles        =\n| Heismans         =\n| AllAmericans     = 10\n| uniform          =\n| FightSong        = Ever True\n| MascotDisplay    = \n| MarchingBand     = [[Brown University Band]]\n| Rivalries        = [[Rhode Island Rams football|Rhode Island]] ([[Brown\u2013Rhode Island football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />\n}}\n[[File:Cornell-Brown football game 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Brown Bears vs. [[Cornell Big Red football|Cornell]], 20 October 2018]]\n: ''For information on all Brown University sports, see [[Brown Bears]]''\n\nThe '''Brown Bears football''' program is the intercollegiate [[American football]] team for [[Brown University]] located in the U.S. state of [[Rhode Island]]. The team competes in the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS) and are members of the [[Ivy League]]. Brown's first football team was fielded in 1878. The Bears play their home games at the 20,000-seat [[Brown Stadium]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. The team's head coach is [[James Perry (American football)|James Perry]], who was hired on December 3, 2018.\n\n==History==\nIn the middle of the 1926 season, the \u201cIron Men\u201d came into being when the same 11 players played against Yale for 60 minutes and a 7\u20130 win. The next week the same 11 players played without substitution against Dartmouth and won 10\u20130. Two weeks later the Iron Men played 58 minutes against Harvard, but in the last two minutes the substitutes came in to earn their letters. Brown won all its games that year until the Thanksgiving game against Colgate ended in a 10\u201310 tie. The famed \u201cIron Men\u201d were Thurston Towle \u201928, Paul Hodge \u201928, Orland Smith \u201927, Charles Considine \u201928, Lou Farber \u201929, Ed Kevorkian \u201929, Hal Broda \u201927, Al Cornsweet \u201929, Dave Mishel \u201927, Ed Lawrence \u201928, and Roy Randall \u201928. In the 1948 season, Brown fans were the originators of the popular \"de-fense!\" chant that spread to the NFL in the 1950s. Following the [[1981 NCAA Division I-A football season|1981 season]], the Ivy League was reclassified to [[Division I-AA]], today known as the [[Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS), Brown moved to Division I-AA play with the rest of the league.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/17/sports/ncaafootball/17ivy.html?ei=5088&en=eef43e83c884e0f3&ex=1321419600&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&pagewanted=print New York Times] \u2013 2006-11-17</ref> Brown has 607 wins, making them tied for 72nd all time in wins among division one football programs.   \n\nIn 1997, Phil Estes began a twenty-one year tenure as Brown's head coach, resulting in three Ivy League championships. In 2018, after two consecutive winless seasons in the Ivy League, Estes announced that he would be stepping down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25324886/phil-estes-steps-brown-bears-coach|title=Estes steps down as Brown's coach|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Championships ==\nThe Bears have no national championships, though they do have one undefeated team, the [[1926 Brown Bears football team|1926 team]], also known as the Iron Men of 1926, finishing 9\u20130\u20131 (and winning all three of their Ivy League games), with a 10\u201310 tie with [[Colgate Raiders football|Colgate]] in the last game of the season. \n\n===Conference championships===\nThe Bears have won the Ivy League title four times in their history. The Bears won their first Ivy League title in 1976, sharing it with Yale while finishing 8\u20131 on the season, clinching the title with a 28\u201317 victory over Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/1976_champions|title=Ivy League Championships|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 1999, the Bears went 9\u20131 (the most victories since 1926, along with a record seven game winning streak), while beating Columbia 23\u20136 to share the Ivy League title with Yale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/1999_champions|title=Ivy League Championships|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 2005, the Bears finished 9\u20131, beating Columbia 52\u201321 in their final game in order to clinch their first ever outright Ivy League title and third overall. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/2005_champions|title=Ivy League Championship Teams|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 2008, the Bears finished 7\u20133 (while losing only one Ivy League game), beating Columbia 41\u201310 to clinch a share of the Ivy League title, their fourth over conference title and third in nine years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/2008_champions|title=Ivy League Championship Teams|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/fball/2015-16/media_guide/15fbguide-YearbyYearHistory.pdf|website=Ivy League}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Brown Bears|Year|Conference|Coach|Overall record|Conference record}}\n|-\n| 1976 || [[Ivy League]] || [[John W. Anderson (American football)|John W. Anderson]] || 8\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 1999 || Ivy League || [[Phil Estes]] || 9\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 2005 || Ivy League || Phil Estes || 9\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 2008 || Ivy League || Phil Estes || 7\u20133 || 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==Bowl games==\nBrown has made one bowl appearance, garnering a record of 0\u20131.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Brown Bears|Season|Date|Bowl|Coach|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n|[[1915 Brown Bears football team|1915]] || January 1, 1916 ||[[1916 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] || [[Eddie N. Robinson]] ||[[1915 Washington State football team|Washington State]] || L 0\u201314 \n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n\n===Rhode Island===\n{{main article|Brown\u2013Rhode Island football rivalry}}\n{{expand section|date=September 2018}}\nBrown leads the series with [[Rhode Island Rams football|Rhode Island]] 73\u201327\u20132.\n\n==College Football Hall of Famers==\n* [[John Heisman]] (1887\u20131889, elected in 1954)\n* [[Tuss McLaughry]] (1926\u20131940, elected in 1962)\n* [[Fritz Pollard]] (1915\u20131916, elected in 1954)\n* [[Eddie N. Robinson]] (played 1892\u20131895; coached 1904\u20131907, 1910\u20131925, elected in 1955)\n* [[Wallace Wade]] (1914\u20131916, elected in 1955)\n\n==Notable former players==\n{{see also|List of Brown Bears in the NFL Draft}}\n* [[Zak DeOssie]]\n* [[James Develin]]\n* [[John Heisman]]\n* [[Steve Jordan (American football)|Steve Jordan]]\n* [[Bob Margarita]]\n* [[Sean Morey (American football)|Sean Morey]]\n* [[Bill O'Brien (American_football)|Bill O'Brien]]\n* [[Joe Paterno]]\n* [[Fritz Pollard]]\n* [[George Pyne]]\n* [[Kyle Rowley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Brown Bears football navbox}}\n{{Brown University}}\n{{Ivy League football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown Bears Football}}\n[[Category:Brown Bears football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1878]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| CurrentSeason   = 2019 Brown Bears football team\n| TeamName         = Brown Bears football\n| Image            = Brown Bears wordmark.png\n| ImageSize        = 100\n| HeadCoach = James Perry\n| HeadCoachYear    = 1st\n| HCWins           = 1\n| HCLosses         = 5\n| Stadium          = [[Brown Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity     = 20,000\n| StadSurface      = [[Grass]]\n| Location         = [[Providence, Rhode Island]] \n| NCAAdivision     = I FCS\n| Conference = [[Ivy League]]\n| FirstYear        = 1878\n| AthleticDirector = Jack Hayes\n| WebsiteName      = BrownBears.com\n| WebsiteURL       = http://brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/index\n| ATWins           = 607\n| ATLosses         = 565\n| ATTies           = 40\n| BowlWins         = 0\n| BowlLosses       = 1\n| BowlTies         = \n| NatlTitles       =\n| ConfTitles       = 4\n| DivTitles        =\n| Heismans         =\n| AllAmericans     = 10\n| uniform          =\n| FightSong        = Ever True\n| MascotDisplay    = \n| MarchingBand     = [[Brown University Band]]\n| Rivalries        = [[Rhode Island Rams football|Rhode Island]] ([[Brown\u2013Rhode Island football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />\n}}\n[[File:Cornell-Brown football game 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Brown Bears vs. [[Cornell Big Red football|Cornell]], 20 October 2018]]\n: ''For information on all Brown University sports, see [[Brown Bears]]''\n\nThe '''Brown Bears football''' program is the intercollegiate [[American football]] team for [[Brown University]] located in the U.S. state of [[Rhode Island]]. The team competes in the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS) and are members of the [[Ivy League]]. Brown's first football team was fielded in 1878. The Bears play their home games at the 20,000-seat [[Brown Stadium]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. The team's head coach is James Perry, who was hired on December 3, 2018.\n\n==History==\nIn the middle of the 1926 season, the \u201cIron Men\u201d came into being when the same 11 players played against Yale for 60 minutes and a 7\u20130 win. The next week the same 11 players played without substitution against Dartmouth and won 10\u20130. Two weeks later the Iron Men played 58 minutes against Harvard, but in the last two minutes the substitutes came in to earn their letters. Brown won all its games that year until the Thanksgiving game against Colgate ended in a 10\u201310 tie. The famed \u201cIron Men\u201d were Thurston Towle \u201928, Paul Hodge \u201928, Orland Smith \u201927, Charles Considine \u201928, Lou Farber \u201929, Ed Kevorkian \u201929, Hal Broda \u201927, Al Cornsweet \u201929, Dave Mishel \u201927, Ed Lawrence \u201928, and Roy Randall \u201928. In the 1948 season, Brown fans were the originators of the popular \"de-fense!\" chant that spread to the NFL in the 1950s. Following the [[1981 NCAA Division I-A football season|1981 season]], the Ivy League was reclassified to [[Division I-AA]], today known as the [[Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS), Brown moved to Division I-AA play with the rest of the league.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/17/sports/ncaafootball/17ivy.html?ei=5088&en=eef43e83c884e0f3&ex=1321419600&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&pagewanted=print New York Times] \u2013 2006-11-17</ref> Brown has 607 wins, making them tied for 72nd all time in wins among division one football programs.   \n\nIn 1997, Phil Estes began a twenty-one year tenure as Brown's head coach, resulting in three Ivy League championships. In 2018, after two consecutive winless seasons in the Ivy League, Estes announced that he would be stepping down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25324886/phil-estes-steps-brown-bears-coach|title=Estes steps down as Brown's coach|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Championships ==\nThe Bears have no national championships, though they do have one undefeated team, the [[1926 Brown Bears football team|1926 team]], also known as the Iron Men of 1926, finishing 9\u20130\u20131 (and winning all three of their Ivy League games), with a 10\u201310 tie with [[Colgate Raiders football|Colgate]] in the last game of the season. \n\n===Conference championships===\nThe Bears have won the Ivy League title four times in their history. The Bears won their first Ivy League title in 1976, sharing it with Yale while finishing 8\u20131 on the season, clinching the title with a 28\u201317 victory over Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/1976_champions|title=Ivy League Championships|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 1999, the Bears went 9\u20131 (the most victories since 1926, along with a record seven game winning streak), while beating Columbia 23\u20136 to share the Ivy League title with Yale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/1999_champions|title=Ivy League Championships|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 2005, the Bears finished 9\u20131, beating Columbia 52\u201321 in their final game in order to clinch their first ever outright Ivy League title and third overall. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/2005_champions|title=Ivy League Championship Teams|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> In 2008, the Bears finished 7\u20133 (while losing only one Ivy League game), beating Columbia 41\u201310 to clinch a share of the Ivy League title, their fourth over conference title and third in nine years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownbears.com/sports/m-footbl/fb_history/2008_champions|title=Ivy League Championship Teams|author=|date=|website=brownbears.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/fball/2015-16/media_guide/15fbguide-YearbyYearHistory.pdf|website=Ivy League}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Brown Bears|Year|Conference|Coach|Overall record|Conference record}}\n|-\n| 1976 || [[Ivy League]] || [[John W. Anderson (American football)|John W. Anderson]] || 8\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 1999 || Ivy League || [[Phil Estes]] || 9\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 2005 || Ivy League || Phil Estes || 9\u20131 || 6\u20131\n|-\n| 2008 || Ivy League || Phil Estes || 7\u20133 || 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==Bowl games==\nBrown has made one bowl appearance, garnering a record of 0\u20131.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Brown Bears|Season|Date|Bowl|Coach|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n|[[1915 Brown Bears football team|1915]] || January 1, 1916 ||[[1916 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] || [[Eddie N. Robinson]] ||[[1915 Washington State football team|Washington State]] || L 0\u201314 \n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n\n===Rhode Island===\n{{main article|Brown\u2013Rhode Island football rivalry}}\n{{expand section|date=September 2018}}\nBrown leads the series with [[Rhode Island Rams football|Rhode Island]] 73\u201327\u20132.\n\n==College Football Hall of Famers==\n* [[John Heisman]] (1887\u20131889, elected in 1954)\n* [[Tuss McLaughry]] (1926\u20131940, elected in 1962)\n* [[Fritz Pollard]] (1915\u20131916, elected in 1954)\n* [[Eddie N. Robinson]] (played 1892\u20131895; coached 1904\u20131907, 1910\u20131925, elected in 1955)\n* [[Wallace Wade]] (1914\u20131916, elected in 1955)\n\n==Notable former players==\n{{see also|List of Brown Bears in the NFL Draft}}\n* [[Zak DeOssie]]\n* [[James Develin]]\n* [[John Heisman]]\n* [[Steve Jordan (American football)|Steve Jordan]]\n* [[Bob Margarita]]\n* [[Sean Morey (American football)|Sean Morey]]\n* [[Bill O'Brien (American_football)|Bill O'Brien]]\n* [[Joe Paterno]]\n* [[Fritz Pollard]]\n* [[George Pyne]]\n* [[Kyle Rowley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Brown Bears football navbox}}\n{{Brown University}}\n{{Ivy League football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown Bears Football}}\n[[Category:Brown Bears football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1878]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "link toJames Perry (American football)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brown_Bears_football"}
{"title_page": "R. Budd Dwyer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|American politician noted for his public suicide at a news conference}}\n{{redirect-confuse|Budd Dwyer|Buddy Dyer}}\n{{other people||Robert Dwyer (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Robert Budd Dwyer\n| image = R. Budd Dwyer.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Dwyer, circa January 1986\n| order = 30th\n| office = Treasurer of Pennsylvania\n| term_start = January 20, 1981\n| term_end = January 22, 1987\n| governor = [[Dick Thornburgh]]<br />[[Bob Casey Sr.]]\n| predecessor = Robert E. Casey\n| successor = [[G. Davis Greene, Jr.]]\n| state_senate2 = Pennsylvania\n| district2 = [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 50|50th]]\n| constituency2 = Parts of [[Mercer County, Pennsylvania|Mercer]], [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford]], and [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie]] Counties<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=Senate Members \"D\"|publisher=Wilkes University|work=Wilkes University Election Statistics Project|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/SD.html}}</ref>\n| term_start2 = January 5, 1971\n| term_end2 = January 20, 1981<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=Pennsylvania Senate - 1981\u20131981|work=[[Wilkes University Election Statistics Project]]|publisher=Wilkes University|year=2004|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/165S.pdf}}</ref>\n| predecessor2 = [[James E. Willard|James Willard]]\n| successor2 = [[Roy Wilt]]\n| state_house3 = Pennsylvania\n| district3 = [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 6|6th]]\n| constituency3 = Parts of [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford County]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=House Members \"D\"|publisher=Wilkes University|work=[[Wilkes University Election Statistics Project]]|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/D.html}}</ref>\n| term_start3 = January 7, 1969\n| term_end3 = November 30, 1970\n| predecessor3 = District Created\n| successor3 = [[H. Harrison Haskell, II|Harrison Haskell]]\n| state_house4 = Pennsylvania\n| district4 = [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford County]]\n| term_start4 = January 5, 1965\n| term_end4 = November 30, 1968\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| birth_name = Robert Budd Dwyer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1939|11|21|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Charles, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|01|22|1939|11|21}}\n| death_place = [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_cause = [[Gunshot suicide|Suicide by gunshot]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Joanne Grappy|1963|1987|reason=his death}}\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Allegheny College]]\n| profession = Teacher, politician\n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Budd Dwyer''' (November 21, 1939&nbsp;\u2013 January 22, 1987) was the 30th [[Pennsylvania Treasurer|State Treasurer]] of the Commonwealth of [[Pennsylvania]]. He served from 1965 to 1971 as a Republican member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] and from 1971 to 1981 as a member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] representing the state's [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 50|50th district]]. He then served as the 30th Treasurer of Pennsylvania from January 20, 1981, until he committed suicide during a press conference.\n\nIn the early 1980s, Pennsylvania discovered its state workers had overpaid federal taxes due to errors in state withholding prior to Dwyer's administration. A multi-million-dollar recovery contract was required to determine the compensation to be given to each employee. In 1986, Dwyer was convicted \nfor accepting a bribe from the California firm that won the contract. He was found guilty on 11 counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, perjury and interstate transportation in aid of racketeering, and was scheduled to be sentenced on January 23, 1987.\n\nOn January 22, 1987, Dwyer called a news conference in the Pennsylvania state capital of [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] where he killed himself in front of the gathered reporters, by shooting himself with a [[.357 Magnum]] revolver.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DEFDF1638F930A15752C0A961948260|title=Official calls in press and kills himself|last=Stevens|first=William K.|date=January 23, 1987|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 11, 2008}}</ref> Dwyer's [[suicide]] was broadcast later that day to a wide television audience across Pennsylvania.\n\nThroughout Dwyer's trial and after his conviction, Dwyer maintained that he was not guilty of the charges for which he was convicted, and that his conviction resulted from political persecution. In 2010, the prosecution's main witness, [[William Trickett Smith]], maintained that his testimony at Dwyer's 1986 trial\u2014 in which he stated that he offered Dwyer a bribe, and that Dwyer accepted this offer\u2014  was truthful, and that he had committed perjury at his own 1985 trial when he denied offering Dwyer a bribe.<ref name=\"Honest Man\">{{Cite web|url = http://dwyermovie.com/|title = Honest Man: The Life of R.Budd Dwyer (documentary movie)|date = 2010|accessdate = |website = |publisher = Eighty Four Films|last = |first =}}</ref> Moreover, Smith stated in October 1984\u2014 the year before his own trial\u2014 that he offered Dwyer a bribe, and that Dwyer accepted it.<ref name=\"Latrobe\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42456853/latrobe_bulletin/|title=New evidence challenges Dwyer|last=Morris|first=David|date=February 18, 1987|work=Latrobe Bulletin|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|pages=4}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer family photograph.jpg|thumb|Dwyer with his family]]\nR. Budd Dwyer was born on November 21, 1939, in [[St. Charles, Missouri]].<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> Dwyer graduated in 1961 with a A.B. in political science and accounting from [[Allegheny College]]<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q_9KAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Budd+Dwyer%22+%22November+21,+1939%22|title=The Pennsylvania Manual|last=Department of General Services|date=1972|publisher=Pennsylvania Bureau of Publications|volume=101|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he was a member of the Beta Chi chapter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetachi.org/beta-chi|title=Beta Chi {{!}} Theta Chi|website=www.thetachi.org|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> of [[Theta Chi|Theta Chi Fraternity]].<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /><ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> After earning a [[master's degree]]<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> in education<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> in 1963,<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> he taught social studies and coached [[American football|football]]<ref name=\"McHugh\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQHaCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|title=Political Suicide: Missteps, Peccadilloes, Bad Calls, Backroom Hijinx, Sordid Pasts, Rotten Breaks, and Just Plain Dumb Mistakes in the Annals of American Politics|last=McHugh|first=Erin|date=April 15, 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|isbn=978-1-68177-117-5|pages=30|language=en}}</ref> at [[Cambridge Springs, Pennsylvania|Cambridge Springs High School]].<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer with Gerald Ford.jpg|thumb|Dwyer in the 1970s, with U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]]]]\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer swearing in as Pennsylvanian state treasurer, 1984.jpg|thumb|Dwyer in 1984, being sworn in for his second term as Pennsylvania state treasurer]]\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Dwyer became active in politics.<ref name=\"McHugh\" /> He was elected to the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] from the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 6|6th]] district (although seats were apportioned by county before 1969) in 1964 and was reelected in 1966 and 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/D.html|title=House Members \"D\"|website=staffweb.wilkes.edu|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> In 1970, while still a sitting State Representative, Dwyer ran for a seat in the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] from its 50th district and won.<ref name=\"wilkes\">{{Cite web|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/SD.html|title=Senate Members \"D\"|website=staffweb.wilkes.edu|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Shortly after his victory he resigned his seat in the State House and was sworn in as Senator in January 1971.<ref name=\"wilkes\" />\n\nAfter being elected to additional terms in 1974 and 1978,<ref name=\"wilkes\" /> Dwyer decided to try for a state office and in 1980 ran for and won the office of [[Pennsylvania Treasurer]]<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> that had been held by [[Robert E. Casey]] since 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fandm.edu/uploads/files/218862118495841122-1996-row-office-elections.pdf|title=1996 Row Office Elections|last=Madonna|first=G. Terry|last2=Yost|first2=Berwood|date=|website=Franklin and Marshall College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=548956|title=Our Campaigns - PA Treasurer Race - Nov 04, 1980|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> He ran for a second and last term in 1984 and won reelection to the seat.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n===Bribery investigation and conviction===\nFrom 1979 to 1981, before Dwyer was state treasurer, public employees of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania overpaid millions of dollars in [[Federal Insurance Contributions Act tax|Federal Insurance Contributions Act]] (FICA).<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/26/us/pennsylvania-aide-focus-of-scandal.html|title=Pennsylvania Aide Focus of Scandal|date=August 26, 1984|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As a result, the state required an accounting firm to determine refunds for its employees.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/26/us/pennsylvania-aide-focus-of-scandal.html|title=Pennsylvania Aide Focus of Scandal|date=August 26, 1984|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The no-bid US$4.6 million contract was awarded to Computer Technology Associates (CTA), a [[California]]-based firm, owned by John Torquato, Jr, a native of Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, in May 1984.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\" /> Later, Pennsylvania Governor [[Dick Thornburgh]] received an anonymous memo detailing allegations of bribery that occurred during the awarding of the contract. Upon learning that the FBI was investigating the circumstances of the awarding of the CTA contract, it was cancelled by Dwyer on July 11, 1984.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\" /> \n\nAn investigation was undertaken by [[United States Department of Justice|federal]] [[United States Attorney|prosecutors]]. Dwyer allegedly tried to divert and forestall this investigation, stating that the US attorney had neither the authority nor evidence to pursue prosecution.<ref>Jenkins,Philip (1993) The C.T.A. case: A study in political corruption, \"Crime, Law and Social Change\" 19: 329-351</ref> Dwyer later admitted to telling his staff to withhold request for proposal (RFP) information from the U.S. Attorney and the FBI during the investigation.<ref name=\"West trial highlights\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/dlug0s5pzorcsbk/James_West_trial_highlights_6-12-85.pdf?dl=0|title=James_West_trial_highlights_6-12-85.pdf|website=Dropbox|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer was finally charged with agreeing to receive a [[Kickback (bribery)|kickback]] of $300,000 in return for awarding CTA the contract. Prior to Dwyer's indictment, The U.S. Attorney indicted Torquato, Torquato's attorney William T. Smith, and Smith's wife. At Smith's 1985 trial, Smith testified that Torquato offered Dwyer a campaign contribution in return for the CTA contract, yet Dwyer rejected Torquato's offer. In contrast, Torquato testified that it was Smith who offered Dwyer $300,000 in return for the CTA contract. Dwyer, acting as a defense witness for Smith at Smith's trial, denied that he was offered any contribution at all.<ref>\"CTA trial's outcome revives corruption probe\" The Philadelphia Inquirer(Philadelphia, Pennsylvania), June 26, 1985</ref> However, prior to Smith's trial,  on October 27, 1984 (four days after Smith's indictment), Smith confessed to offering Dwyer a bribe, and stated that Dwyer accepted this offer.<ref name=\"Latrobe\" />\n\n{{quote| I met with Dwyer in his office and at the insistence of Torquato offered to give him $300,000 if he signed a contract with CTA LTD. Dwyer talked about $100,000 to him personally--$100,000 to his campaign committee--$100,000 to Republican State Committee.  [Dwyer] was going to see Robert Asher in Montgomery County that weekend to talk to him about how this should be done.<https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352//>}}\n\nHowever, [[Robert B. Asher|Bob Asher]], the then Republican Party Chairman for the State of Pennsylvania, objected to this, and requested that the $300 000 be directed entirely to the Republican State Committee, since Asher \"did not want Dwyer to go to jail\". <ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352/</ref> \n\n{{quote|[Asher] indicated that he had had a conversation with Mr. Dwyer, and he knew that I had made an offer to him of a $300,000 contribution, and then he was very angry when he began to talk about that, angry with me. Said he thought I knew better than to offer a contribution to Mr. Dwyer, and he said if there was going to be a contribution, it was going to go to Republican State Committee.<https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352//>}}\n\nDwyer, along with Asher, were indicted by a federal grand jury on May 13, 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42457882/p_16a/|title=Friends of ex-GOP chairman will help pay CTA legal bill|date=June 5, 1986|work=The Times Leader|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Associated Press|pages=16A}}</ref> In the hopes of reducing his twelve year sentence stemming from his 1985 conviction, Smith testified on behalf of the federal government against Dwyer and Asher at their 1986 trial. Ultimately, Smith did not receive any reduction in his sentence for testifying against Dwyer (although his wife, Judy Smith, was granted immunity from prosecution).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/us-v-smith-1568|title=U.S. v. Smith, 839 F.2d 175 (3d Cir. 1988)|website=Casetext|url-status=live|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> \n\n\nIt was revealed at Dwyer's trial that Dwyer sought and won approval for special legislation\u2014 Act 38 of 1984 (House Bill 1397)\u2014  that authorized him to recover the FICA overpayments, and that coded computer tape seized from CTA's office in July 1984 that showed that Dwyer was to receive a $300,000 pay-off for awarding CTA the contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jury hears closing arguments in CTA Bribery Conspiracy Trial |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_XBeAAAAIBAJ&pg=1077%2C1989816 |publisher=Observer-Reporter |accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Smith and Torquato's claims about Dwyer being bribed were corroborated by four independent and impartial witnesses,<ref>\"CTA Case heads to Jury\" The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 13, 1986. https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=99QbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KmMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6193%2C2280060</ref> and Smith's testimony against Dwyer was virtually identical to written statements Smith made long before entering into a plea agreement.<ref>\"CTA defence throws doubt on witnesses\" Pittsburgh Post-Gazette&nbsp;\u2014 December 13, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BYBIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5W0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3388%2C5382972</ref> Dwyer maintained that he awarded CTA the contract on the basis of his treasury task force recommendation, yet this conflicted with the fact that Dwyer personally handled all matters relating to the contract six days prior to awarding it to CTA;<ref name=\"DwyerIndictment\">[https://www.dropbox.com/s/v8p2mz0824pe5gi/Dwyer_Indictment.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - Dwyer_Indictment.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> furthermore, his task force's contribution merely consisted in the making of a single phone call to David I. Herbert (the former State Director for Social Security, who controlled FICA recovery for Pennsylvania's public employees, and who was subsequently convicted for conspiring with CTA).<ref name=\"West trial highlights\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/news/2019/03/ex-state_official_who_has_held.html|title=Ex-state official who held elected office learns he's not allowed to run again|first=John|last=Beauge|date=March 15, 2019|website=PennLive|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer awarded the contract to CTA\u2014an obscure California firm with three employees and little equipment\u2014despite being informed in May 1984 by the major Pennsylvania-based accounting firm Arthur Young and Associates (who had two hundred and fifty employees and submitted a proposal eight days prior to CTA's proposal) that they could perform the FICA recovery as fast as CTA for half the cost.\n<ref name=\"DwyerIndictment\" /><ref name=\"news.google.com\">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v8pRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4G0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6108%2C196013 Pittsburgh Post-Gazette - Google News Archive Search<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\"Post-Gazette1985-05-13\">\u201cLawyer\u2019s challenge task force\u2019s CTA selection,\u201d Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania)May 13, 1985</ref>\nCharles Collins, Arthur Young's former director of Management Consulting in Pittsburgh, testified at Dwyer's trial that Arthur Young and Associates was prepared to negotiate the FICA recovery contract (that was half the cost of the CTA contract) and that Dwyer was clearly aware of Arthur Young's position before committing the contract to CTA. Additionally, sixteen other competitors were willing to be considered for the FICA recovery contract and many had communicated with Treasurer Dwyer's office to request an opportunity to bid on the contract, yet Dwyer did not respond.<ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352/</ref> Dwyer stated he awarded the contract to CTA (via his task force's recommendation) on the basis of CTA's providing \"immediate credit\", yet the contract between CTA and Dwyer contained no information regarding CTA's ability to provide such credit.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BuddDwyer/1372927-0_-_File_1_-_Section_2_djvu.txt Full text of \"Budd Dwyer\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/ukfw5zvd8t5px7g/CTA_Contract.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - CTA_Contract.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Moreover, Dwyer admitted that he did not mention the concept of \"immediate credit\" to Arthur Young and Associates when officials from the firm asked why CTA was chosen over them.<ref name=\"Post-Gazette1985-05-13\" />\n   \nNevertheless, Dwyer denied any wrongdoing, stating that after the CTA contract was signed, Smith merely made a \"generic\" offer to help him with his campaign <ref name=\"West trial highlights\" />. Dwyer's lawyer spoke to the prosecutor, acting U.S. Attorney West, asking him if he would drop all charges against Dwyer if Dwyer resigned as state treasurer. West declined the offer. He instead [[plea bargain|offered]] to let Dwyer plead guilty to a single charge of [[bribery|bribe receiving]], which would have meant up to a maximum of five years' imprisonment, as long as he resigned from his office as Treasurer of Pennsylvania and cooperated fully with the government's investigation, but Dwyer refused and went to trial. At his trial, Dwyer did not take the stand, and his lawyer, Paul Killion, presented no defense witnesses<ref name=\"news.google.com\" /> since he thought that the government did not sufficiently prove its case.<ref>The Pittsburgh Press - Dec 13, 1986</ref> It is possible that Dwyer did not testify in his own defense since he did not want to be questioned regarding his involvement in a 1980 conspiracy (involving Dwyer's wife's business \"Poli-Ed,\" and two [[Pennsylvania State Education Association]] (PSEA) employees) in which he allegedly siphoned money from his campaign into his personal funds.<ref>Observer-Reporter - Aug 30, 1984</ref><ref>Jenkins,Philip (1993) The C.T.A. case: A study in political corruption, \"Crime, Law and Social Change\" 19: 329-351.</ref><ref>Keisling, William (2003). The Sins of Our Fathers (2011 ed.). Yardbird Books</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 1986, Dwyer was found guilty on 11 counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, perjury and interstate transportation in aid of racketeering, and consequently faced a sentence of up to 55 years imprisonment and a $300,000 fine.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\">{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DW9eAAAAIBAJ&pg=1346%2C2427748|title = Dwyer must resign or face dismissal, Zimmerman says|last = |first = |date = January 22, 1987|work = Observer-Reporter|access-date = November 8, 2015|via =}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-27/news/26190720_1_plea-bargaining-memorial-service-funeral|title=700 Attend Services For Dwyer Treasurer Recalled As 'Righteous Man'|last=Cusick|first=Frederick|date=January 27, 1987|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|url-status=usurped|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717204304/http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-27/news/26190720_1_plea-bargaining-memorial-service-funeral|archive-date=July 17, 2015|accessdate=November 8, 2015}}</ref> His sentencing was scheduled for January 23, 1987, to be performed by U.S. District Court Judge [[Malcolm Muir (judge)|Malcolm Muir]].<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /> One mail-fraud charge against Dwyer was dismissed by Judge Muir.<ref>\"Dwyer defense rests, One charge out in CTA trial\" The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 9, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=89QbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KmMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324%2C42021</ref> One juror, Carolyn Edwards of Williamsport, found it emotionally difficult to convict Dwyer (and Asher) since they were men of \"very high integrity ... they just made a mistake\".<ref>\"CTA Prove to Continue\", The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 19, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_yQeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G5YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6441%2C1878698</ref> [[Robert B. Asher|Bob Asher]], Dwyer's co-defendant, was sentenced to one year in jail. He later returned to politics and served as a Republican national committeeman for Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"famouspictures\" />\n\n===Dwyer's status as state treasurer===\nPennsylvania law stated that Dwyer could not officially be removed from office until his sentencing in January.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> Given this, Dwyer stated that until his legal appeal was resolved, he would stay on as Treasurer under leave of absence without pay and would not resign before having the opportunity to appeal his conviction.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> In the interim, the treasury department would be run by Deputy Treasurer Donald L. Johnson.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" />\n\nDwyer continued to profess his innocence after being convicted, as did others close to him.<ref name=\"famouspictures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famouspictures.org/mag/index.php?title=Budd_Dwyer|title=Famous Pictures Magazine&nbsp;\u2014 Budd Dwyer|author=Lucas, Dean}}</ref> On December 23, he wrote a letter to President [[Ronald Reagan]] seeking a presidential pardon,<ref>{{cite web|year=2010|url=http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf|title=Article Highlight: Budd's letter to Reagan.|format=''Honest Man'' (Film)|publisher=dwyermovie.com|accessdate=January 30, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004010706/http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf|archivedate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> and to [[Arlen Specter|Senator Arlen Specter]] seeking support in this effort.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\" />\n\nThe week of Dwyer's sentencing, Pennsylvania State Attorney General Leroy Zimmerman and state prosecutors were investigating a provision of the Pennsylvania state constitution where removal of a civil worker from office who has been convicted of a crime is \"self-executing\", thus, automatic upon that person's sentencing. A decision confirming this constitutional point was expected on January 22, the day before Dwyer's sentencing hearing.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lgc.state.pa.us/getfile.cfm?file=/Reports/deskbook14/Issues-Governance08-Removal-from-Office.pdf|title = Removal From Office|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref>\n\n==Public suicide==\nIn a meeting in his home, Dwyer discussed the idea of a press conference with his press secretary James \"Duke\" Horshock and Deputy Treasurer Don Johnson, on January 15, 1987. At the time, Johnson cautioned Dwyer not to use such a forum to attack the governor or other individuals involved with his criminal conviction, and Dwyer assured him that he would not do so. Both men left assuming Dwyer would ultimately resign if the press conference were held.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\">{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rSQeAAAAIBAJ&pg=6259%2C3216975|title = He searched in vain for help: State treasurer spent last days seeking peace|last = |first = |date = January 23, 1987|work = The Pittsburgh Press|access-date = November 11, 2015|via =}}</ref>\n\nDwyer finally reached Senator Specter by telephone on January 21, two days before his sentencing. A Specter aide stated that the two of them talked for 8-to-10 minutes.<ref name=\"mcall\">{{Cite web|title = Dwyer Sought Specter's Help To Get A Presidential Pardon|url = http://articles.mcall.com/1987-01-24/news/2566807_1_dwyer-specter-s-office-sen-arlen-specter|website = tribunedigital-mcall|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref> Following up on his letter to the senator asking for help, he personally wrote to President [[Ronald Reagan]] asking for a presidential pardon. In his letter, Dwyer once again professed his innocence and stated that the concept of immediate credit was not understood by the uneducated, unsophisticated \"rural\" jury at his trial.<ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/vfo2qprhx21rsn7/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The senator responded that this request to President Reagan was \"not realistic\" because the judicial process, including appeals, had not yet run its course.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\">{{Cite web|title = Dwyer Rejected Deal, Later Sought Pardon|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-24/news/26186955_1_dwyer-specter-plea|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"mcall\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Treasurer may have saved pension for wife|url = http://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/01/23/Treasurer-may-have-saved-pension-for-wife/9732538376400/|website = UPI|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, Dwyer asked his press secretary Horshock and deputy press secretary Gregory Penny to set up a news conference for the next day without telling them what he was to discuss.<ref>{{cite web|last1 = Kaminski|first1 = Joseph|title = Case Study: R. Budd Dwyer's Suicide|url = http://josephkaminski.org/2015/12/29/r-budd-dwyer/}}</ref><ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\">{{Cite web|title = Treasurer Dwyer Kills Self Suicide At News Session|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-23/news/26186493_1_treasurer-dwyer-state-computer-contract-federal-charges|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 8, 2015}}</ref> Horshock arranged the press conference for 10:30&nbsp;a.m. EST the next day, January 22. The press secretary called dozens of reporters asking them to attend, and told them he did not know its subject.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /><ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\nInitially, Dwyer wanted to ban certain reporters from the press conference who he believed wrote biased accounts about him and even suggested that a guard should be in attendance to prevent entry to those who were not on his authorized list. Horshock, who was unconvinced about Dwyer's claims that he was being conspired against, objected, stating to Dwyer that he could not \"use state government facilities to manipulate the free flow of information\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=90MgAAAAIBAJ&pg=4854,2153889|title=The Bitter End of R. Budd Dwyer|last=|first=|date=|website=The Pittsburgh Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the press conference, acting U.S. Attorney West, who had secured the conviction against Dwyer, remarked that the Treasurer's resignation \"sounds like the appropriate thing to do under the circumstances. It seems like it would save everybody a lot of time and aggravation.\"<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /> Similarly, Harrisburg ''[[Patriot-News]]'' reporter Kenn Marshall described the consensus among reporters: they would be attending to see Dwyer announce his resignation from office. \"My mission was to stay there until he said those words, then call in a new top for our story.\"<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\">{{cite news|author=Dunkle, David N.|title=Former Pennsylvania Treasurer R. Budd Dwyer's controversial death re-examined in new film|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2010/11/former_pennsylvania_treasurer.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xrEvFmeP?url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2010/11/former_pennsylvania_treasurer.html|archivedate=April 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe night before the press conference, Dwyer wrote the following note:\n\n{{quote|I enjoy being with Jo so much, the next 20 years or so would have been wonderful. Tomorrow is going to be so difficult and I hope I can go through with it.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />}}\n\n===Dwyer's press statement===\nThe next morning, Dwyer went to his press conference as planned. Appearing nervous and agitated, he again professed his innocence and began reading from a 21-page prepared text later described as a \"rambling polemic about the criminal justice system\".<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\" /> It singled out former Governor Thornburgh, Acting U.S. Attorney West, agents in the FBI, Judge Muir, and others for tarnishing the justice system and ruining him.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\" /> Dwyer stated that Attorney West purposely had Dwyer's trial not in Harrisburg but in Williamsport, since in Williamsport the jury pool was the most uneducated in the state of Pennsylvania.<ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/sao4iw2mrb76693/Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Dwyer spoke out against the death penalty and expressed regret for voting in favor of it while he was in the Pennsylvania assembly. This speech lasted nearly 30 minutes, and approximately halfway into it, with no apparent end in sight, some of the gathered press began to pack up and leave. Dwyer spotted this and interrupted himself to say, \"Those of you who are putting your cameras away, I think you ought to stay because we're not, we're not finished yet.\"<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\nGiven the inflammatory nature of portions of Dwyer's text, press secretary Horshock had considered interrupting him outright to stop him but concluded that he would hold his own press conference after Dwyer's. \"I had to make it known that I was not aware of the content of the statement. I didn't want it to be thought that I wrote that for him.\"<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" />\n\nUpon reaching the final page of his statement, which had not been distributed to the press nor press secretary Horshock in advance, Dwyer paused. \"...and I'm on the last page now, and I don't have enough to pass out, but Duke [Horshock], I'll leave this here, and you can make copies for the people; there's a few extra copies here right now.\"<ref>Video containing audio of final words ([http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6686827830708949101 link])</ref> Dwyer continued,\n\n{{quote|I thank the good Lord for giving me 47 years of exciting challenges, stimulating experiences, many happy occasions and most of all[,] the finest wife and children any man could ever desire.\n\nNow my life has changed for no apparent reason. People who call and write are exasperated and feel helpless. They know I am innocent and want to help, but in this nation, the worlds [''sic''] greatest democracy, there is nothing they can do to prevent me from being punished for a crime they know I did not commit. Some who have called have said that I am a modern day [[Job (biblical figure)|Job]].\n\nJudge Muir is also noted for his medieval sentences. I face a maximum sentence of 55 years in prison and a $305,000 fine for being innocent. Judge Muir has already told the press that he felt \"invigorated\" when we were found guilty and that he plans to imprison me as a \"deterrant\" to other public officials. But it wouldn't be a deterrant [''sic''] because every public official who knows me knows that I am innocent. It wouldn't be legitimate punishment because I've done nothing wrong. Since I'm a victim of political persecution, my prison would simply be an American [[Gulag]].\n\nI ask those that believe in me to continue to extend friendship and prayer to my family, to work untiringly for the creation of a true justice system here in the United States, and to press on with the efforts to vindicate me, so that my family and their future families are not tainted by this injustice that has been perpetrated on me.\n\nWe were confident that right and truth would prevail and I would be acquitted and we would devote the rest of our lives working to create a justice system here in the United States. The guilty verdict has strengthened that resolve. But as we've discussed our plans to expose the warts of our legal system[,] people have said, 'Why bother? No one cares, you'll look foolish, ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[20/20 (US television show)|20/20]]'', the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], [[Jack Anderson (columnist)|Jack Anderson]], and others have been publicizing cases like yours for years and it doesn't bother anyone.'}}\n\nAt this point, Dwyer stopped reading from his prepared remarks, with the gathered press still waiting on his expected resignation. There was still a significant portion remaining, which detailed what he was actually planning to do, and it read as follows:\n\n{{quote|I've repeatedly said that I'm not going to resign as State Treasurer. After many hours of thought and meditation I've made a decision that should not be an example to anyone because it is unique to my situation. Last May I told you that after the trial, I would give you the story of the decade. To those of you who are shallow, the events of this morning will be that story. But to those of you with depth and concern the real story will be what I hope and pray results from this morning\u2013in the coming months and years[,] the development of a true justice system here in the United States. I am going to die in office in an effort to ' ... see if the shame[-ful] facts, spread out in all their shame, will not burn through our civic shamelessness and set fire to American pride.' Please tell my story on every radio and television station and in every newspaper and magazine in the U.S.. Please leave immediately if you have a weak stomach or mind since I don't want to cause physical or mental distress. Joanne, Rob, DeeDEe [''sic''] - I love you! Thank you for making my life so happy. Good bye to you all on the count of 3. Please make sure that the sacrifice of my life is not in vain.}}\n\nAfter deciding to break from his speech, Dwyer called to three of his staffers, giving each a sealed envelope with the insignia of the treasury department.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" /> The first envelope, given to [[Bob Holste]], contained a letter addressed to then-Pennsylvania Governor [[Robert P. Casey|Bob Casey]], who had taken office just two days earlier. The second, given to deputy press secretary Gregory Penny, contained an [[organ donation|organ donor]] card and other related materials. The last, given to Deputy Treasurer Don Johnson, contained materials intended for Dwyer's family, including three letters: one for his wife Joanne, and one for each of his children, Rob and DeeDee (Dyan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42446760/p_26/|title=Son says Dwyer innocent of charge|date=January 23, 1987|work=The York Dispatch|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=UPI|pages=26}}</ref>), and suggested funeral arrangements.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" /><ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\nFreelance photographer Gary Miller, one of the reporters in attendance, describes the scene to this point, \"It was just kind of a long-winded, sad event.\"<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\" />\n\n==={{anchor|Suicide}}Public suicide===\nAfter he had finished speaking and handing out the notes to his staffers, Dwyer then produced a [[manila paper|manila envelope]] with a [[Bluing (steel)|blued]] [[Smith & Wesson Model 27]] [[.357 Magnum]] revolver in it. When the crowd in the room saw what Dwyer had pulled out of the envelope, the mood changed immediately from one of waiting to see whether he would resign his office to one of panic as nobody knew what he was planning to do with the gun. People gasped, and Dwyer backed up against the wall, pointing the weapon into the air. Dwyer calmly stated to his audience, \"Please, please leave the room if this will ... if this will affect you.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Witnesses to Tragedy|first=Laura|last=Muha|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/103854256.html?dids=103854256:103854256&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+21%2C+1988&author=By+Laura+Muha&pub=Newsday+%28Combined+editions%29&desc=THE+PRESS+Witnesses+to+Tragedy+The+suicide+of+Pennsylvania+Treasurer+R.+Budd+Dwyer+a+year+ago+stirred+horror+and+introspection+in+the+reporters+who+saw+it&pqatl=google|format=Newspaper archive|newspaper=Newsday|location=Long Island|date=January 21, 1988|page=3|quote=When he saw Dwyer's gun, he dashed from the room calling for help}} Text Word Count: 1290</ref>\n\nSome people in the room left to call for help. Among those who stayed, some pleaded with Dwyer to surrender the gun while others tried to approach him and seize the weapon. Dwyer warned against either action, exclaiming in his final words, \"Don't, don't, don't, this will hurt someone. Sit down.\u201d<ref name=\"AP1-23\">\"PA. Treasurer Kills Self at News Conference\", ''Associated Press'', January 23, 1987.</ref> A moment later, Dwyer quickly fired one shot into his mouth and collapsed to the floor, dead.<ref>{{harvnb|Grossman|2003|p=108}}</ref> Five news cameras recorded the events. One of the cameras remained focused on Dwyer and captured close up footage of the aftermath of the shooting; as his body slumped, blood streamed from the exit wound in the back of his head as well as from his nostrils and mouth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://documentslide.com/download/link/media-ethics-and-the-fourth-commandment-the-case-of-robert-budd-dwyer-pennsylvania|title=The Case of Robert Budd Dwyer, Pennsylvania State Treasurer|date=January 1, 2015|publisher=www.documentslide.com|quote=The bullet exited out of the top of his head, leaving a bloody stream ... as more blood flowed through his nostrils and from the exit wound.|accessdate=December 3, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220224926/http://documentslide.com/download/link/media-ethics-and-the-fourth-commandment-the-case-of-robert-budd-dwyer-pennsylvania|archivedate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Horshock took the podium and asked the media to leave and for someone to call for medical assistance and the police.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDwyer died instantly from the gunshot shortly before 11:00 a.m. EST but was not pronounced dead until 11:31 a.m.<ref name=\"AP1-23\" /> An aide later stated that Dwyer's corneas were made available for transplant per his organ donation wishes, but that no other organs were usable by the time his body reached a hospital.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\n===Graphic footage and television media===\nMany television stations throughout Pennsylvania broadcast taped footage of Dwyer's suicide to a midday audience. Philadelphia station [[WPVI-TV|WPVI]] (Channel 6) showed Dwyer pulling the trigger and falling backwards, but did not show the bullet path.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447122/daily_magazine_p_1d/|title=How TV covered the Dwyer suicide|last=Bianculli|first=David|date=January 23, 1987|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Shister|first2=Gail|department=Daily Magazine|pages=1D, [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447127/daily_magazine_p_8d/ 8D]}}</ref> Over the next several hours, news editors had to decide how much of the graphic footage to air. Many chose not to air the final moments of the suicide and WPVI also chose not to show the gunshot a second time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447103/p_26/|title=Did TV cover suicide right?|date=January 23, 1987|work=The York Dispatch|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=UPI|pages=26}}</ref>\n\nMany stations, including [[WCAU-TV|WCAU]] and Pennsylvania's [[Westinghouse Broadcasting|Group W]] stations [[KYW-TV|KYW]] and [[KDKA-TV|KDKA]], froze the action just before the gunshot. However, the latter two allowed the audio of the shooting to continue under the frozen image. Group W's news cameraman William L. \"Bill\" Martin and reporter David Sollenberger had a camera set up at the conference. They chose to air the audio with a freeze-frame of the gun in Dwyer's mouth. Only a handful aired the unedited press conference. [[WPVI-TV|WPVI]] in [[Philadelphia]] re-broadcast the suicide footage in full on their 5&nbsp;p.m. and 6&nbsp;p.m. [[Action News]] broadcast without warning the viewers. That station's broadcast is a source for copies circulating on the Internet. [[WPXI-TV|WPXI]] in [[Pittsburgh]] is reported by the [[Associated Press]] to have broadcast the footage uncensored on an early newscast. In explaining the decision to air, WPXI operations manager By Williams said, \"It's an important event [about] an important man.\" Williams avoided airing the footage in the evening newscasts, explaining, \"Everyone knows by then that he did it. There are children out of school.\"<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Pictures Raise News Issue|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE2D71138F930A15752C0A961948260|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 23, 1987|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref> However, in central Pennsylvania, many children were home from school during the day of Dwyer's suicide due to a snowstorm.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> Harrisburg TV station [[WHTM-TV]] opted to broadcast uncut video of the suicide twice that day, defending the decision (despite hundreds of viewer complaints afterward) due to the important nature of the story.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMany older students reacted to the event by creating [[black comedy]] jokes similar to those that circulated after the ''[[Space Shuttle Challenger|Challenger]]'' [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|disaster]]. A study of the incidence of the jokes showed that they were told only in areas where stations showed uncensored footage of the press conference.<ref>[[Simon Bronner]], \"Political Suicide: The Budd Dwyer Joke Cycle and the Humor of Disaster.\" ''Midwestern Folklore'' 14 (1988): 81\u201389.</ref> At least one reporter present at Dwyer's suicide suffered from being a witness. [[Tony Romeo (reporter)|Tony Romeo]], a radio reporter, was standing a few feet from Dwyer. After the suicide, Romeo developed [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] and took a break from journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=413|title=Feeling the Heat|last=Soteropoulos|first=Jacqueline|date=December 2000|work=[[American Journalism Review]]|accessdate=August 5, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925161656/http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=413|archive-date=September 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Letter to Governor Bob Casey===\nDwyer's deep mistrust of outgoing Republican Governor Thornburgh was spelled out in detail in his press conference statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf|title = Dwyer, Final Statements, Press Conference, Pennsylvania Treasurer's Office|date = January 22, 1987|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Dwyer|first = R. Budd}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> The timing of Dwyer's press conference and suicide meant that Thornburgh was not empowered to appoint a Treasurer to replace him. Instead, this fell to Thornburgh's successor, Democrat Bob Casey, who had taken office on January 20.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Casey Vows Political Open Door 5,000 View Inaugural Ceremony|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-21/news/26191261_1_robert-p-casey-ceremonies-new-governor|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe letter Dwyer had sent to Casey stated, among other things, \"By the time you receive this letter ... the office of State Treasurer of Pennsylvania will be vacant. I stress to you that I did not resign but was State Treasurer of Pennsylvania to the end.\" It also stated that Casey \"will be the great Governor that Pennsylvania needs at this time in our history.\" He suggested his wife Joanne as his successor, describing her as \"very talented, personable, organized and hard-working.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = OFFICIAL CALLS IN PRESS AND KILLS HIMSELF|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/23/us/official-calls-in-press-and-kills-himself.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = January 23, 1987|access-date = November 8, 2015|issn = 0362-4331|first = William K. Stevens, Special To The New York|last = Times}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Casey did not take Dwyer's suggestion. Regardless of the events of January 22, the governor and legislature of Pennsylvania already expected Dwyer to either resign or be removed from office. As such, a deal had already been brokered wherein the next treasurer, a Democrat, would serve out Dwyer's term and step down at its end. This was [[G. Davis Greene Jr.]], who was appointed as the 31st Treasurer of Pennsylvania on January 23, 1987, the day after Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|title = G. Davis Greene Jr., 81, former state treasurer|url = http://articles.philly.com/2012-09-06/news/33617725_1_financial-adviser-state-treasurer-bob-casey|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Response to allegations made by Dwyer in his final press statement===\nFollowing Dwyer's public suicide, the [[National Association of State Treasurers]] called for Dwyer's allegations (contained in his final press statement) to be reviewed by the [[United States Department of Justice]]. After a thorough investigation, the Justice Department's [[Office of Professional Responsibility]] cleared attorney James West and everyone else involved in Dwyer's investigation and prosecution, of any wrongdoing. The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] also investigated Dwyer's claims regarding impropriety on behalf of FBI personnel. They ultimately found Dwyer's claims to be \"lacking in substance and specificity\" and warranting no further action.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/BuddDwyer Budd Dwyer : Federal Bureau of Investigation : Free Download, Borrow, and Streaming : Internet Archive<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Death benefits===\nSince Dwyer died in office, his widow Joanne was able to collect full survivor benefits totaling over $1.28 million, which at the time was the largest death benefit payment ever made by the state system. If Dwyer had been sentenced, state law would have prohibited the payment of his state-provided pension benefits.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /><ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=April 16, 1987 |title=Family to Get $1.28-Million Pension in Suicide of Pennsylvania Official |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-751_1_pension-benefit |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025022622/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-751_1_pension-benefit |archive-date=October 25, 2015}}</ref> A spokesman for Dwyer suggested that he may have killed himself to preserve the pension benefits for his family, whose finances had been ruined by legal defense costs.<ref>\"Pennsylvania Official's Suicide May Be Linked to Finances\", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', January 24, 1987.</ref> Other statements made by friends and family also suggest that this was Dwyer's motivation.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n==Appeals==\nOn January 27, 1987, Dwyer's lawyers filed an appeal in the [[U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Pennsylvania]] seeking the dismissal of all post-trial motions that were then pending against Dwyer, abatement of Dwyer's conviction and the dismissal of his May 13, 1986 indictment. On March 5, 1987, the district court denied all motions, and ordered to \"close this file as to R. Budd Dwyer.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/654/1254/1690114/|title=United States v. Dwyer, 654 F. Supp. 1254 (M.D. Pa. 1987)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer's lawyers appealed this decision, and [[The US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] subsequently vacated the judgement. On remand, the district court was instructed to dismiss Dwyer's motions (since the Court lacked subject matter jurisdiction) and Dwyer's convictions for mail fraud and conspiracy were upheld. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/855/144/372541/|title=United States of America v. Dwyer, R. Budd, Appellant, 855 F.2d 144 (3d Cir. 1988)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Six years after Dwyer's death, efforts were made to clear Dwyer's name when a retrial request was filed in U.S. District Court in July 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/6cffa3fdd182b37efd86fa3b18677837|title=Six Years After Suicide, New Trial Sought To Clear Budd Dwyer|date=July 26, 1993|website=AP News|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> This request was denied in October of the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42459010/judge_turns_down_motion_for_dwyer/|title=Judge turns down motion for Dwyer retrial|date=October 28, 1993|work=Indiana Gazette|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Associate Press}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*The 1988 [[Rapeman]] EP ''[[Budd (EP)|Budd]]'' is named after Dwyer, and its first track, which shares the EP's name, contains lyrics referencing his suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.touchandgorecords.com/bands/band.php?id=63|title=Rapeman: Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records|accessdate=June 8, 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Faith No More]]'s 1992 ''[[Angel Dust (Faith No More album)|Angel Dust]]'' b-side \"The World Is Yours\" samples audio of Dwyer's suicide.\n*[[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]]'s debut single \"[[Get Your Gunn]]\" (1994) samples audio of Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/marilyn-manson-i-like-to-smoke-and-hang-out-with-the-gangsta-rappers-6615701|title=Marilyn Manson: \"I Like To Smoke and Hang Out With The Gangsta Rappers\"|last=Louvau|first=Jim|date=May 30, 2013|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 1995 song \"[[Hey Man Nice Shot]]\" by the band [[Filter (band)|Filter]] is about Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://klaq.com/richard-patrick-of-filter-talks-about-hey-man-nice-shot-and-kurt-cobain/|title=Richard Patrick of Filter Talks About 'Hey Man Nice Shot' and Kurt Cobain|work=[[KLAQ]]|last=Adams|first=Buzz|date=June 29, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n*The 1999 album ''[[Volume 1 (CKY album)|Volume 1]]'' by Pennsylvania [[alternative rock]] band [[CKY (band)|CKY]] initially featured an artistic depiction of Dwyer committing suicide. When the band later signed with [[Volcom]], the album art was changed as the label found the graphic to be too offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/future-shock-she-wants-revenge-the-donnas-cky-and-more-6595143|title=Future Shock: She Wants Revenge, The Donnas, CKY, and more|last=D'Andrea|first=Nika|date=August 17, 2007|website=[[Phoenix New Times]]|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}<</ref>\n*The 2002 documentary film ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'' includes footage of Dwyer's suicide as part of a montage of gun-related video clips.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/bowling-for-columbine/oclc/224200985?referer=di&ht=edition|title=Bowling for Columbine|date=2002|oclc=224200985|quote=Abstract:...Footage of and interviews with: ...R. Budd Dwyer (handgun suicide whose death was televised in the U.S.)...|medium=film}}</ref>\n* In 2003, the band [[Ion Dissonance]] featured a song called \"The Bud Dwyer Effect\" on their album ''[[Breathing Is Irrelevant]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathing-is-irrelevant-mw0000317092|title=Breathing Is Irrelevant - Ion Dissonance|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2006 film ''[[Loren Cass]]'' shows footage of Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Loren Cass|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/loren-cass-1200558580/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Koehler|first=Robert|date=June 13, 2007|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*The 2010 documentary ''[[Honest Man: The Life of R. Budd Dwyer]]'' by director James Dirschberger detailed the events of the CTA scandal that led to Dwyer's suicide.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n* On their 2013 album ''Hellbound'', New Jersey [[Deathcore]] band [[Fit for an Autopsy]] paid homage to Dwyer in their song \"Thank You, Budd Dwyer\". The band stated that the song was in response to the injustices in the legal system and maintained that Dwyer was a victim of wrongful accusations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fit For An Autopsy Thank Budd Dwyer|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2013/09/04/fit-for-an-autopsy-thank-budd-dwyer/|website=[[MetalSucks]]|last=Rosenberg|first=Axl|date=September 4, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*The cover art for [[Suicideboys]]' 2017 EP, ''Kill Yourself Part III: The Budd Dwyer Saga'', features a still frame of Dwyer with the gun in his mouth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.napster.com/artist/suicideboys/album/kill-yourself-part-iii-the-budd-dwyer-saga|title=Kill Yourself Part III: The Budd Dwyer Saga|website=Napster|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Grossman|first=Mark|title=Political corruption in America: an encyclopedia of scandals, power, and greed|url=https://archive.org/details/politicalcorrupt0000gros/page/108|url-access=registration|edition=2003|pages=108|year=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-060-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Keisling|first=William|title=The Sins of Our Fathers|edition=2011|year=2003|publisher=Yardbird Books|isbn=978-0-9620251-0-5}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Yuhasz |first1=Lorraine |title=The Dwyer Case |date=1998 |publisher=Friends of Dwyer Committee |isbn=978-1882611140 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6129|R. Budd Dwyer}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert E. Casey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Pennsylvania Treasurer|Treasurer of Pennsylvania]]|years=1981\u20131987}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[G. Davis Greene, Jr.]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dwyer, Budd}}\n[[Category:R. Budd Dwyer| ]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Allegheny College alumni]]\n[[Category:American politicians who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Educators from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Filmed suicides]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pennsylvania House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania state senators]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Meadville, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from St. Charles, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of corruption in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of mail and wire fraud]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of racketeering]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Organ transplant donors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:Educators from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|American politician noted for his public suicide at a news conference}}\n{{redirect-confuse|Budd Dwyer|Buddy Dyer}}\n{{other people||Robert Dwyer (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Robert Budd Dwyer\n| image = R. Budd Dwyer.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Dwyer, circa January 1986\n| order = 30th\n| office = Treasurer of Pennsylvania\n| term_start = January 20, 1981\n| term_end = January 22, 1987\n| governor = [[Dick Thornburgh]]<br />[[Bob Casey Sr.]]\n| predecessor = Robert E. Casey\n| successor = [[G. Davis Greene, Jr.]]\n| state_senate2 = Pennsylvania\n| district2 = [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 50|50th]]\n| constituency2 = Parts of [[Mercer County, Pennsylvania|Mercer]], [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford]], and [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie]] Counties<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=Senate Members \"D\"|publisher=Wilkes University|work=Wilkes University Election Statistics Project|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/SD.html}}</ref>\n| term_start2 = January 5, 1971\n| term_end2 = January 20, 1981<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=Pennsylvania Senate - 1981\u20131981|work=[[Wilkes University Election Statistics Project]]|publisher=Wilkes University|year=2004|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/165S.pdf}}</ref>\n| predecessor2 = [[James E. Willard|James Willard]]\n| successor2 = [[Roy Wilt]]\n| state_house3 = Pennsylvania\n| district3 = [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 6|6th]]\n| constituency3 = Parts of [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford County]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Harold|title=House Members \"D\"|publisher=Wilkes University|work=[[Wilkes University Election Statistics Project]]|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/D.html}}</ref>\n| term_start3 = January 7, 1969\n| term_end3 = November 30, 1970\n| predecessor3 = District Created\n| successor3 = [[H. Harrison Haskell, II|Harrison Haskell]]\n| state_house4 = Pennsylvania\n| district4 = [[Crawford County, Pennsylvania|Crawford County]]\n| term_start4 = January 5, 1965\n| term_end4 = November 30, 1968\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| birth_name = Robert Budd Dwyer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1939|11|21|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Charles, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|01|22|1939|11|21}}\n| death_place = [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_cause = [[Gunshot suicide|Suicide by gunshot]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Joanne Grappy|1963|1987|reason=his death}}\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Allegheny College]]\n| profession = Teacher, politician\n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Budd Dwyer''' (November 21, 1939&nbsp;\u2013 January 22, 1987) was the 30th [[Pennsylvania Treasurer|State Treasurer]] of the Commonwealth of [[Pennsylvania]]. He served from 1965 to 1971 as a Republican member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] and from 1971 to 1981 as a member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] representing the state's [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 50|50th district]]. He then served as the 30th Treasurer of Pennsylvania from January 20, 1981, until he committed suicide during a press conference.\n\nIn the early 1980s, Pennsylvania discovered its state workers had overpaid federal taxes due to errors in state withholding prior to Dwyer's administration. A multi-million-dollar recovery contract was required to determine the compensation to be given to each employee. In 1986, Dwyer was convicted \nfor accepting a bribe from the California firm that won the contract. He was found guilty on 11 counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, perjury and interstate transportation in aid of racketeering, and was scheduled to be sentenced on January 23, 1987.\n\nOn January 22, 1987, Dwyer called a news conference in the Pennsylvania state capital of [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] where he killed himself in front of the gathered reporters, by shooting himself with a [[.357 Magnum]] revolver.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DEFDF1638F930A15752C0A961948260|title=Official calls in press and kills himself|last=Stevens|first=William K.|date=January 23, 1987|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 11, 2008}}</ref> Dwyer's [[suicide]] was broadcast later that day to a wide television audience across Pennsylvania.\n\nThroughout Dwyer's trial and after his conviction, Dwyer maintained that he was not guilty of the charges for which he was convicted, and that his conviction resulted from political persecution. In 2010, the prosecution's main witness, [[William Trickett Smith]], maintained that his testimony at Dwyer's 1986 trial\u2014 in which he stated that he offered Dwyer a bribe, and that Dwyer accepted this offer\u2014  was truthful, and that he had committed perjury at his own 1985 trial when he denied offering Dwyer a bribe.<ref name=\"Honest Man\">{{Cite web|url = http://dwyermovie.com/|title = Honest Man: The Life of R.Budd Dwyer (documentary movie)|date = 2010|accessdate = |website = |publisher = Eighty Four Films|last = |first =}}</ref> Moreover, Smith stated in October 1984\u2014 the year before his own trial\u2014 that he offered Dwyer a bribe, and that Dwyer accepted it.<ref name=\"Latrobe\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42456853/latrobe_bulletin/|title=New evidence challenges Dwyer|last=Morris|first=David|date=February 18, 1987|work=Latrobe Bulletin|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|pages=4}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer family photograph.jpg|thumb|Dwyer with his family]]\nR. Budd Dwyer was born on November 21, 1939, in [[St. Charles, Missouri]].<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> Dwyer graduated in 1961 with a A.B. in political science and accounting from [[Allegheny College]]<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q_9KAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Budd+Dwyer%22+%22November+21,+1939%22|title=The Pennsylvania Manual|last=Department of General Services|date=1972|publisher=Pennsylvania Bureau of Publications|volume=101|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he was a member of the Beta Chi chapter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetachi.org/beta-chi|title=Beta Chi {{!}} Theta Chi|website=www.thetachi.org|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> of [[Theta Chi|Theta Chi Fraternity]].<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /><ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> After earning a [[master's degree]]<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> in education<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> in 1963,<ref name=\"DeptGenServices\" /> he taught social studies and coached [[American football|football]]<ref name=\"McHugh\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQHaCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|title=Political Suicide: Missteps, Peccadilloes, Bad Calls, Backroom Hijinx, Sordid Pasts, Rotten Breaks, and Just Plain Dumb Mistakes in the Annals of American Politics|last=McHugh|first=Erin|date=April 15, 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|isbn=978-1-68177-117-5|pages=30|language=en}}</ref> at [[Cambridge Springs, Pennsylvania|Cambridge Springs High School]].<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer with Gerald Ford.jpg|thumb|Dwyer in the 1970s, with U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]]]]\n[[File:R. Budd Dwyer swearing in as Pennsylvanian state treasurer, 1984.jpg|thumb|Dwyer in 1984, being sworn in for his second term as Pennsylvania state treasurer]]\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Dwyer became active in politics.<ref name=\"McHugh\" /> He was elected to the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] from the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 6|6th]] district (although seats were apportioned by county before 1969) in 1964 and was reelected in 1966 and 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/D.html|title=House Members \"D\"|website=staffweb.wilkes.edu|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> In 1970, while still a sitting State Representative, Dwyer ran for a seat in the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] from its 50th district and won.<ref name=\"wilkes\">{{Cite web|url=http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/SD.html|title=Senate Members \"D\"|website=staffweb.wilkes.edu|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Shortly after his victory he resigned his seat in the State House and was sworn in as Senator in January 1971.<ref name=\"wilkes\" />\n\nAfter being elected to additional terms in 1974 and 1978,<ref name=\"wilkes\" /> Dwyer decided to try for a state office and in 1980 ran for and won the office of [[Pennsylvania Treasurer]]<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> that had been held by [[Robert E. Casey]] since 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fandm.edu/uploads/files/218862118495841122-1996-row-office-elections.pdf|title=1996 Row Office Elections|last=Madonna|first=G. Terry|last2=Yost|first2=Berwood|date=|website=Franklin and Marshall College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=548956|title=Our Campaigns - PA Treasurer Race - Nov 04, 1980|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> He ran for a second and last term in 1984 and won reelection to the seat.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n===Bribery investigation and conviction===\nFrom 1979 to 1981, before Dwyer was state treasurer, public employees of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania overpaid millions of dollars in [[Federal Insurance Contributions Act tax|Federal Insurance Contributions Act]] (FICA).<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/26/us/pennsylvania-aide-focus-of-scandal.html|title=Pennsylvania Aide Focus of Scandal|date=August 26, 1984|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As a result, the state required an accounting firm to determine refunds for its employees.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/08/26/us/pennsylvania-aide-focus-of-scandal.html|title=Pennsylvania Aide Focus of Scandal|date=August 26, 1984|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The no-bid US$4.6 million contract was awarded to Computer Technology Associates (CTA), a [[California]]-based firm, owned by John Torquato, Jr, a native of Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, in May 1984.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\" /> Later, Pennsylvania Governor [[Dick Thornburgh]] received an anonymous memo detailing allegations of bribery that occurred during the awarding of the contract. Upon learning that the FBI was investigating the circumstances of the awarding of the CTA contract, it was cancelled by Dwyer on July 11, 1984.<ref name=\"nytimes1984-08-26\" /> \n\nAn investigation was undertaken by [[United States Department of Justice|federal]] [[United States Attorney|prosecutors]]. Dwyer allegedly tried to divert and forestall this investigation, stating that the US attorney had neither the authority nor evidence to pursue prosecution.<ref>Jenkins,Philip (1993) The C.T.A. case: A study in political corruption, \"Crime, Law and Social Change\" 19: 329-351</ref> Dwyer later admitted to telling his staff to withhold request for proposal (RFP) information from the U.S. Attorney and the FBI during the investigation.<ref name=\"West trial highlights\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/dlug0s5pzorcsbk/James_West_trial_highlights_6-12-85.pdf?dl=0|title=James_West_trial_highlights_6-12-85.pdf|website=Dropbox|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer was finally charged with agreeing to receive a [[Kickback (bribery)|kickback]] of $300,000 in return for awarding CTA the contract. Prior to Dwyer's indictment, The U.S. Attorney indicted Torquato, Torquato's attorney William T. Smith, and Smith's wife. At Smith's 1985 trial, Smith testified that Torquato offered Dwyer a campaign contribution in return for the CTA contract, yet Dwyer rejected Torquato's offer. In contrast, Torquato testified that it was Smith who offered Dwyer $300,000 in return for the CTA contract. Dwyer, acting as a defense witness for Smith at Smith's trial, denied that he was offered any contribution at all.<ref>\"CTA trial's outcome revives corruption probe\" The Philadelphia Inquirer(Philadelphia, Pennsylvania), June 26, 1985</ref> However, prior to Smith's trial,  on October 27, 1984 (four days after Smith's indictment), Smith confessed to offering Dwyer a bribe, and stated that Dwyer accepted this offer.<ref name=\"Latrobe\" />\n\n{{quote| I met with Dwyer in his office and at the insistence of Torquato offered to give him $300,000 if he signed a contract with CTA LTD. Dwyer talked about $100,000 to him personally--$100,000 to his campaign committee--$100,000 to Republican State Committee.  [Dwyer] was going to see Robert Asher in Montgomery County that weekend to talk to him about how this should be done.<https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352//>}}\n\nHowever, [[Robert B. Asher|Bob Asher]], the then Republican Party Chairman for the State of Pennsylvania, objected to this, and requested that the $300 000 be directed entirely to the Republican State Committee, since Asher \"did not want Dwyer to go to jail\". <ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352/</ref> \n\n{{quote|[Asher] indicated that he had had a conversation with Mr. Dwyer, and he knew that I had made an offer to him of a $300,000 contribution, and then he was very angry when he began to talk about that, angry with me. Said he thought I knew better than to offer a contribution to Mr. Dwyer, and he said if there was going to be a contribution, it was going to go to Republican State Committee.<https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352//>}}\n\nDwyer, along with Asher, were indicted by a federal grand jury on May 13, 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42457882/p_16a/|title=Friends of ex-GOP chairman will help pay CTA legal bill|date=June 5, 1986|work=The Times Leader|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Associated Press|pages=16A}}</ref> In the hopes of reducing his twelve year sentence stemming from his 1985 conviction, Smith testified on behalf of the federal government against Dwyer and Asher at their 1986 trial. Ultimately, Smith did not receive any reduction in his sentence for testifying against Dwyer (although his wife, Judy Smith, was granted immunity from prosecution).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/us-v-smith-1568|title=U.S. v. Smith, 839 F.2d 175 (3d Cir. 1988)|website=Casetext|url-status=live|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> \n\n\nIt was revealed at Dwyer's trial that Dwyer sought and won approval for special legislation\u2014 Act 38 of 1984 (House Bill 1397)\u2014  that authorized him to recover the FICA overpayments, and that coded computer tape seized from CTA's office in July 1984 that showed that Dwyer was to receive a $300,000 pay-off for awarding CTA the contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jury hears closing arguments in CTA Bribery Conspiracy Trial |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_XBeAAAAIBAJ&pg=1077%2C1989816 |publisher=Observer-Reporter |accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Smith and Torquato's claims about Dwyer being bribed were corroborated by four independent and impartial witnesses,<ref>\"CTA Case heads to Jury\" The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 13, 1986. https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=99QbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KmMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6193%2C2280060</ref> and Smith's testimony against Dwyer was virtually identical to written statements Smith made long before entering into a plea agreement.<ref>\"CTA defence throws doubt on witnesses\" Pittsburgh Post-Gazette&nbsp;\u2014 December 13, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BYBIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5W0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3388%2C5382972</ref> Dwyer maintained that he awarded CTA the contract on the basis of his treasury task force recommendation, yet this conflicted with the fact that Dwyer personally handled all matters relating to the contract six days prior to awarding it to CTA;<ref name=\"DwyerIndictment\">[https://www.dropbox.com/s/v8p2mz0824pe5gi/Dwyer_Indictment.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - Dwyer_Indictment.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> furthermore, his task force's contribution merely consisted in the making of a single phone call to David I. Herbert (the former State Director for Social Security, who controlled FICA recovery for Pennsylvania's public employees, and who was subsequently convicted for conspiring with CTA).<ref name=\"West trial highlights\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/news/2019/03/ex-state_official_who_has_held.html|title=Ex-state official who held elected office learns he's not allowed to run again|first=John|last=Beauge|date=March 15, 2019|website=PennLive|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer awarded the contract to CTA\u2014an obscure California firm with three employees and little equipment\u2014despite being informed in May 1984 by the major Pennsylvania-based accounting firm Arthur Young and Associates (who had two hundred and fifty employees and submitted a proposal eight days prior to CTA's proposal) that they could perform the FICA recovery as fast as CTA for half the cost.\n<ref name=\"DwyerIndictment\" /><ref name=\"news.google.com\">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v8pRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4G0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6108%2C196013 Pittsburgh Post-Gazette - Google News Archive Search<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\"Post-Gazette1985-05-13\">\u201cLawyer\u2019s challenge task force\u2019s CTA selection,\u201d Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania)May 13, 1985</ref>\nCharles Collins, Arthur Young's former director of Management Consulting in Pittsburgh, testified at Dwyer's trial that Arthur Young and Associates was prepared to negotiate the FICA recovery contract (that was half the cost of the CTA contract) and that Dwyer was clearly aware of Arthur Young's position before committing the contract to CTA. Additionally, sixteen other competitors were willing to be considered for the FICA recovery co tract and many had communicated with the Treasurer Dwyer's office to request an opportunity to bid on the contract, yet Dwyer did not respond.<ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/854/1483/222352/</ref> Dwyer stated he awarded the contract to CTA (via his task force's recommendation) on the basis of CTA's providing \"immediate credit\", yet the contract between CTA and Dwyer contained no information regarding CTA's ability to provide such credit.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BuddDwyer/1372927-0_-_File_1_-_Section_2_djvu.txt Full text of \"Budd Dwyer\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/ukfw5zvd8t5px7g/CTA_Contract.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - CTA_Contract.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Moreover, Dwyer admitted that he did not mention the concept of \"immediate credit\" to Arthur Young and Associates when officials from the firm asked why CTA was chosen over them.<ref name=\"Post-Gazette1985-05-13\" />\n   \nNevertheless, Dwyer denied any wrongdoing, stating that after the CTA contract was signed, Smith merely made a \"generic\" offer to help him with his campaign <ref name=\"West trial highlights\" />. Dwyer's lawyer spoke to the prosecutor, acting U.S. Attorney West, asking him if he would drop all charges against Dwyer if Dwyer resigned as state treasurer. West declined the offer. He instead [[plea bargain|offered]] to let Dwyer plead guilty to a single charge of [[bribery|bribe receiving]], which would have meant up to a maximum of five years' imprisonment, as long as he resigned from his office as Treasurer of Pennsylvania and cooperated fully with the government's investigation, but Dwyer refused and went to trial. At his trial, Dwyer did not take the stand, and his lawyer, Paul Killion, presented no defense witnesses<ref name=\"news.google.com\" /> since he thought that the government did not sufficiently prove its case.<ref>The Pittsburgh Press - Dec 13, 1986</ref> It is possible that Dwyer did not testify in his own defense since he did not want to be questioned regarding his involvement in a 1980 conspiracy (involving Dwyer's wife's business \"Poli-Ed,\" and two [[Pennsylvania State Education Association]] (PSEA) employees) in which he allegedly siphoned money from his campaign into his personal funds.<ref>Observer-Reporter - Aug 30, 1984</ref><ref>Jenkins,Philip (1993) The C.T.A. case: A study in political corruption, \"Crime, Law and Social Change\" 19: 329-351.</ref><ref>Keisling, William (2003). The Sins of Our Fathers (2011 ed.). Yardbird Books</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 1986, Dwyer was found guilty on 11 counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, perjury and interstate transportation in aid of racketeering, and consequently faced a sentence of up to 55 years imprisonment and a $300,000 fine.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\">{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DW9eAAAAIBAJ&pg=1346%2C2427748|title = Dwyer must resign or face dismissal, Zimmerman says|last = |first = |date = January 22, 1987|work = Observer-Reporter|access-date = November 8, 2015|via =}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-27/news/26190720_1_plea-bargaining-memorial-service-funeral|title=700 Attend Services For Dwyer Treasurer Recalled As 'Righteous Man'|last=Cusick|first=Frederick|date=January 27, 1987|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|url-status=usurped|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717204304/http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-27/news/26190720_1_plea-bargaining-memorial-service-funeral|archive-date=July 17, 2015|accessdate=November 8, 2015}}</ref> His sentencing was scheduled for January 23, 1987, to be performed by U.S. District Court Judge [[Malcolm Muir (judge)|Malcolm Muir]].<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /> One mail-fraud charge against Dwyer was dismissed by Judge Muir.<ref>\"Dwyer defense rests, One charge out in CTA trial\" The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 9, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=89QbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KmMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324%2C42021</ref> One juror, Carolyn Edwards of Williamsport, found it emotionally difficult to convict Dwyer (and Asher) since they were men of \"very high integrity ... they just made a mistake\".<ref>\"CTA Prove to Continue\", The Pittsburgh Press&nbsp;\u2014 December 19, 1986, https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_yQeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G5YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6441%2C1878698</ref> [[Robert B. Asher|Bob Asher]], Dwyer's co-defendant, was sentenced to one year in jail. He later returned to politics and served as a Republican national committeeman for Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"famouspictures\" />\n\n===Dwyer's status as state treasurer===\nPennsylvania law stated that Dwyer could not officially be removed from office until his sentencing in January.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> Given this, Dwyer stated that until his legal appeal was resolved, he would stay on as Treasurer under leave of absence without pay and would not resign before having the opportunity to appeal his conviction.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> In the interim, the treasury department would be run by Deputy Treasurer Donald L. Johnson.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" />\n\nDwyer continued to profess his innocence after being convicted, as did others close to him.<ref name=\"famouspictures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famouspictures.org/mag/index.php?title=Budd_Dwyer|title=Famous Pictures Magazine&nbsp;\u2014 Budd Dwyer|author=Lucas, Dean}}</ref> On December 23, he wrote a letter to President [[Ronald Reagan]] seeking a presidential pardon,<ref>{{cite web|year=2010|url=http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf|title=Article Highlight: Budd's letter to Reagan.|format=''Honest Man'' (Film)|publisher=dwyermovie.com|accessdate=January 30, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004010706/http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf|archivedate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> and to [[Arlen Specter|Senator Arlen Specter]] seeking support in this effort.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\" />\n\nThe week of Dwyer's sentencing, Pennsylvania State Attorney General Leroy Zimmerman and state prosecutors were investigating a provision of the Pennsylvania state constitution where removal of a civil worker from office who has been convicted of a crime is \"self-executing\", thus, automatic upon that person's sentencing. A decision confirming this constitutional point was expected on January 22, the day before Dwyer's sentencing hearing.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lgc.state.pa.us/getfile.cfm?file=/Reports/deskbook14/Issues-Governance08-Removal-from-Office.pdf|title = Removal From Office|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref>\n\n==Public suicide==\nIn a meeting in his home, Dwyer discussed the idea of a press conference with his press secretary James \"Duke\" Horshock and Deputy Treasurer Don Johnson, on January 15, 1987. At the time, Johnson cautioned Dwyer not to use such a forum to attack the governor or other individuals involved with his criminal conviction, and Dwyer assured him that he would not do so. Both men left assuming Dwyer would ultimately resign if the press conference were held.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\">{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rSQeAAAAIBAJ&pg=6259%2C3216975|title = He searched in vain for help: State treasurer spent last days seeking peace|last = |first = |date = January 23, 1987|work = The Pittsburgh Press|access-date = November 11, 2015|via =}}</ref>\n\nDwyer finally reached Senator Specter by telephone on January 21, two days before his sentencing. A Specter aide stated that the two of them talked for 8-to-10 minutes.<ref name=\"mcall\">{{Cite web|title = Dwyer Sought Specter's Help To Get A Presidential Pardon|url = http://articles.mcall.com/1987-01-24/news/2566807_1_dwyer-specter-s-office-sen-arlen-specter|website = tribunedigital-mcall|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref> Following up on his letter to the senator asking for help, he personally wrote to President [[Ronald Reagan]] asking for a presidential pardon. In his letter, Dwyer once again professed his innocence and stated that the concept of immediate credit was not understood by the uneducated, unsophisticated \"rural\" jury at his trial.<ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/vfo2qprhx21rsn7/DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - DwyersLetterToReagan.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The senator responded that this request to President Reagan was \"not realistic\" because the judicial process, including appeals, had not yet run its course.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\">{{Cite web|title = Dwyer Rejected Deal, Later Sought Pardon|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-24/news/26186955_1_dwyer-specter-plea|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"mcall\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Treasurer may have saved pension for wife|url = http://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/01/23/Treasurer-may-have-saved-pension-for-wife/9732538376400/|website = UPI|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, Dwyer asked his press secretary Horshock and deputy press secretary Gregory Penny to set up a news conference for the next day without telling them what he was to discuss.<ref>{{cite web|last1 = Kaminski|first1 = Joseph|title = Case Study: R. Budd Dwyer's Suicide|url = http://josephkaminski.org/2015/12/29/r-budd-dwyer/}}</ref><ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\">{{Cite web|title = Treasurer Dwyer Kills Self Suicide At News Session|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-23/news/26186493_1_treasurer-dwyer-state-computer-contract-federal-charges|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 8, 2015}}</ref> Horshock arranged the press conference for 10:30&nbsp;a.m. EST the next day, January 22. The press secretary called dozens of reporters asking them to attend, and told them he did not know its subject.<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /><ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\nInitially, Dwyer wanted to ban certain reporters from the press conference who he believed wrote biased accounts about him and even suggested that a guard should be in attendance to prevent entry to those who were not on his authorized list. Horshock, who was unconvinced about Dwyer's claims that he was being conspired against, objected, stating to Dwyer that he could not \"use state government facilities to manipulate the free flow of information\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=90MgAAAAIBAJ&pg=4854,2153889|title=The Bitter End of R. Budd Dwyer|last=|first=|date=|website=The Pittsburgh Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the press conference, acting U.S. Attorney West, who had secured the conviction against Dwyer, remarked that the Treasurer's resignation \"sounds like the appropriate thing to do under the circumstances. It seems like it would save everybody a lot of time and aggravation.\"<ref name=\"Zimmerman\" /> Similarly, Harrisburg ''[[Patriot-News]]'' reporter Kenn Marshall described the consensus among reporters: they would be attending to see Dwyer announce his resignation from office. \"My mission was to stay there until he said those words, then call in a new top for our story.\"<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\">{{cite news|author=Dunkle, David N.|title=Former Pennsylvania Treasurer R. Budd Dwyer's controversial death re-examined in new film|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2010/11/former_pennsylvania_treasurer.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xrEvFmeP?url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2010/11/former_pennsylvania_treasurer.html|archivedate=April 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe night before the press conference, Dwyer wrote the following note:\n\n{{quote|I enjoy being with Jo so much, the next 20 years or so would have been wonderful. Tomorrow is going to be so difficult and I hope I can go through with it.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />}}\n\n===Dwyer's press statement===\nThe next morning, Dwyer went to his press conference as planned. Appearing nervous and agitated, he again professed his innocence and began reading from a 21-page prepared text later described as a \"rambling polemic about the criminal justice system\".<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\" /> It singled out former Governor Thornburgh, Acting U.S. Attorney West, agents in the FBI, Judge Muir, and others for tarnishing the justice system and ruining him.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-24\" /> Dwyer stated that Attorney West purposely had Dwyer's trial not in Harrisburg but in Williamsport, since in Williamsport the jury pool was the most uneducated in the state of Pennsylvania.<ref>[https://www.dropbox.com/s/sao4iw2mrb76693/Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf?dl=0 Dropbox - Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf - Simplify your life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Dwyer spoke out against the death penalty and expressed regret for voting in favor of it while he was in the Pennsylvania assembly. This speech lasted nearly 30 minutes, and approximately halfway into it, with no apparent end in sight, some of the gathered press began to pack up and leave. Dwyer spotted this and interrupted himself to say, \"Those of you who are putting your cameras away, I think you ought to stay because we're not, we're not finished yet.\"<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\nGiven the inflammatory nature of portions of Dwyer's text, press secretary Horshock had considered interrupting him outright to stop him but concluded that he would hold his own press conference after Dwyer's. \"I had to make it known that I was not aware of the content of the statement. I didn't want it to be thought that I wrote that for him.\"<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" />\n\nUpon reaching the final page of his statement, which had not been distributed to the press nor press secretary Horshock in advance, Dwyer paused. \"...and I'm on the last page now, and I don't have enough to pass out, but Duke [Horshock], I'll leave this here, and you can make copies for the people; there's a few extra copies here right now.\"<ref>Video containing audio of final words ([http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6686827830708949101 link])</ref> Dwyer continued,\n\n{{quote|I thank the good Lord for giving me 47 years of exciting challenges, stimulating experiences, many happy occasions and most of all[,] the finest wife and children any man could ever desire.\n\nNow my life has changed for no apparent reason. People who call and write are exasperated and feel helpless. They know I am innocent and want to help, but in this nation, the worlds [''sic''] greatest democracy, there is nothing they can do to prevent me from being punished for a crime they know I did not commit. Some who have called have said that I am a modern day [[Job (biblical figure)|Job]].\n\nJudge Muir is also noted for his medieval sentences. I face a maximum sentence of 55 years in prison and a $305,000 fine for being innocent. Judge Muir has already told the press that he felt \"invigorated\" when we were found guilty and that he plans to imprison me as a \"deterrant\" to other public officials. But it wouldn't be a deterrant [''sic''] because every public official who knows me knows that I am innocent. It wouldn't be legitimate punishment because I've done nothing wrong. Since I'm a victim of political persecution, my prison would simply be an American [[Gulag]].\n\nI ask those that believe in me to continue to extend friendship and prayer to my family, to work untiringly for the creation of a true justice system here in the United States, and to press on with the efforts to vindicate me, so that my family and their future families are not tainted by this injustice that has been perpetrated on me.\n\nWe were confident that right and truth would prevail and I would be acquitted and we would devote the rest of our lives working to create a justice system here in the United States. The guilty verdict has strengthened that resolve. But as we've discussed our plans to expose the warts of our legal system[,] people have said, 'Why bother? No one cares, you'll look foolish, ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[20/20 (US television show)|20/20]]'', the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], [[Jack Anderson (columnist)|Jack Anderson]], and others have been publicizing cases like yours for years and it doesn't bother anyone.'}}\n\nAt this point, Dwyer stopped reading from his prepared remarks, with the gathered press still waiting on his expected resignation. There was still a significant portion remaining, which detailed what he was actually planning to do, and it read as follows:\n\n{{quote|I've repeatedly said that I'm not going to resign as State Treasurer. After many hours of thought and meditation I've made a decision that should not be an example to anyone because it is unique to my situation. Last May I told you that after the trial, I would give you the story of the decade. To those of you who are shallow, the events of this morning will be that story. But to those of you with depth and concern the real story will be what I hope and pray results from this morning\u2013in the coming months and years[,] the development of a true justice system here in the United States. I am going to die in office in an effort to ' ... see if the shame[-ful] facts, spread out in all their shame, will not burn through our civic shamelessness and set fire to American pride.' Please tell my story on every radio and television station and in every newspaper and magazine in the U.S.. Please leave immediately if you have a weak stomach or mind since I don't want to cause physical or mental distress. Joanne, Rob, DeeDEe [''sic''] - I love you! Thank you for making my life so happy. Good bye to you all on the count of 3. Please make sure that the sacrifice of my life is not in vain.}}\n\nAfter deciding to break from his speech, Dwyer called to three of his staffers, giving each a sealed envelope with the insignia of the treasury department.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" /> The first envelope, given to [[Bob Holste]], contained a letter addressed to then-Pennsylvania Governor [[Robert P. Casey|Bob Casey]], who had taken office just two days earlier. The second, given to deputy press secretary Gregory Penny, contained an [[organ donation|organ donor]] card and other related materials. The last, given to Deputy Treasurer Don Johnson, contained materials intended for Dwyer's family, including three letters: one for his wife Joanne, and one for each of his children, Rob and DeeDee (Dyan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42446760/p_26/|title=Son says Dwyer innocent of charge|date=January 23, 1987|work=The York Dispatch|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=UPI|pages=26}}</ref>), and suggested funeral arrangements.<ref name=\"PittsburghPress\" /><ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\nFreelance photographer Gary Miller, one of the reporters in attendance, describes the scene to this point, \"It was just kind of a long-winded, sad event.\"<ref name=\"PennLiveNewFilm\" />\n\n==={{anchor|Suicide}}Public suicide===\nAfter he had finished speaking and handing out the notes to his staffers, Dwyer then produced a [[manila paper|manila envelope]] with a [[Bluing (steel)|blued]] [[Smith & Wesson Model 27]] [[.357 Magnum]] revolver in it. When the crowd in the room saw what Dwyer had pulled out of the envelope, the mood changed immediately from one of waiting to see whether he would resign his office to one of panic as nobody knew what he was planning to do with the gun. People gasped, and Dwyer backed up against the wall, pointing the weapon into the air. Dwyer calmly stated to his audience, \"Please, please leave the room if this will ... if this will affect you.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Witnesses to Tragedy|first=Laura|last=Muha|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/103854256.html?dids=103854256:103854256&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+21%2C+1988&author=By+Laura+Muha&pub=Newsday+%28Combined+editions%29&desc=THE+PRESS+Witnesses+to+Tragedy+The+suicide+of+Pennsylvania+Treasurer+R.+Budd+Dwyer+a+year+ago+stirred+horror+and+introspection+in+the+reporters+who+saw+it&pqatl=google|format=Newspaper archive|newspaper=Newsday|location=Long Island|date=January 21, 1988|page=3|quote=When he saw Dwyer's gun, he dashed from the room calling for help}} Text Word Count: 1290</ref>\n\nSome people in the room left to call for help. Among those who stayed, some pleaded with Dwyer to surrender the gun while others tried to approach him and seize the weapon. Dwyer warned against either action, exclaiming in his final words, \"Don't, don't, don't, this will hurt someone. Sit down.\u201d<ref name=\"AP1-23\">\"PA. Treasurer Kills Self at News Conference\", ''Associated Press'', January 23, 1987.</ref> A moment later, Dwyer quickly fired one shot into his mouth and collapsed to the floor, dead.<ref>{{harvnb|Grossman|2003|p=108}}</ref> Five news cameras recorded the events. One of the cameras remained focused on Dwyer and captured close up footage of the aftermath of the shooting; as his body slumped, blood streamed from the exit wound in the back of his head as well as from his nostrils and mouth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://documentslide.com/download/link/media-ethics-and-the-fourth-commandment-the-case-of-robert-budd-dwyer-pennsylvania|title=The Case of Robert Budd Dwyer, Pennsylvania State Treasurer|date=January 1, 2015|publisher=www.documentslide.com|quote=The bullet exited out of the top of his head, leaving a bloody stream ... as more blood flowed through his nostrils and from the exit wound.|accessdate=December 3, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220224926/http://documentslide.com/download/link/media-ethics-and-the-fourth-commandment-the-case-of-robert-budd-dwyer-pennsylvania|archivedate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Horshock took the podium and asked the media to leave and for someone to call for medical assistance and the police.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDwyer died instantly from the gunshot shortly before 11:00 a.m. EST but was not pronounced dead until 11:31 a.m.<ref name=\"AP1-23\" /> An aide later stated that Dwyer's corneas were made available for transplant per his organ donation wishes, but that no other organs were usable by the time his body reached a hospital.<ref name=\"philly-archives1987-01-23\" />\n\n===Graphic footage and television media===\nMany television stations throughout Pennsylvania broadcast taped footage of Dwyer's suicide to a midday audience. Philadelphia station [[WPVI-TV|WPVI]] (Channel 6) showed Dwyer pulling the trigger and falling backwards, but did not show the bullet path.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447122/daily_magazine_p_1d/|title=How TV covered the Dwyer suicide|last=Bianculli|first=David|date=January 23, 1987|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Shister|first2=Gail|department=Daily Magazine|pages=1D, [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447127/daily_magazine_p_8d/ 8D]}}</ref> Over the next several hours, news editors had to decide how much of the graphic footage to air. Many chose not to air the final moments of the suicide and WPVI also chose not to show the gunshot a second time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42447103/p_26/|title=Did TV cover suicide right?|date=January 23, 1987|work=The York Dispatch|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=UPI|pages=26}}</ref>\n\nMany stations, including [[WCAU-TV|WCAU]] and Pennsylvania's [[Westinghouse Broadcasting|Group W]] stations [[KYW-TV|KYW]] and [[KDKA-TV|KDKA]], froze the action just before the gunshot. However, the latter two allowed the audio of the shooting to continue under the frozen image. Group W's news cameraman William L. \"Bill\" Martin and reporter David Sollenberger had a camera set up at the conference. They chose to air the audio with a freeze-frame of the gun in Dwyer's mouth. Only a handful aired the unedited press conference. [[WPVI-TV|WPVI]] in [[Philadelphia]] re-broadcast the suicide footage in full on their 5&nbsp;p.m. and 6&nbsp;p.m. [[Action News]] broadcast without warning the viewers. That station's broadcast is a source for copies circulating on the Internet. [[WPXI-TV|WPXI]] in [[Pittsburgh]] is reported by the [[Associated Press]] to have broadcast the footage uncensored on an early newscast. In explaining the decision to air, WPXI operations manager By Williams said, \"It's an important event [about] an important man.\" Williams avoided airing the footage in the evening newscasts, explaining, \"Everyone knows by then that he did it. There are children out of school.\"<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Pictures Raise News Issue|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE2D71138F930A15752C0A961948260|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 23, 1987|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref> However, in central Pennsylvania, many children were home from school during the day of Dwyer's suicide due to a snowstorm.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /> Harrisburg TV station [[WHTM-TV]] opted to broadcast uncut video of the suicide twice that day, defending the decision (despite hundreds of viewer complaints afterward) due to the important nature of the story.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nMany older students reacted to the event by creating [[black comedy]] jokes similar to those that circulated after the ''[[Space Shuttle Challenger|Challenger]]'' [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|disaster]]. A study of the incidence of the jokes showed that they were told only in areas where stations showed uncensored footage of the press conference.<ref>[[Simon Bronner]], \"Political Suicide: The Budd Dwyer Joke Cycle and the Humor of Disaster.\" ''Midwestern Folklore'' 14 (1988): 81\u201389.</ref> At least one reporter present at Dwyer's suicide suffered from being a witness. [[Tony Romeo (reporter)|Tony Romeo]], a radio reporter, was standing a few feet from Dwyer. After the suicide, Romeo developed [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] and took a break from journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=413|title=Feeling the Heat|last=Soteropoulos|first=Jacqueline|date=December 2000|work=[[American Journalism Review]]|accessdate=August 5, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925161656/http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=413|archive-date=September 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Letter to Governor Bob Casey===\nDwyer's deep mistrust of outgoing Republican Governor Thornburgh was spelled out in detail in his press conference statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://dl.dropbox.com/u/33088283/Virb/Dwyer_Final_Statements.pdf|title = Dwyer, Final Statements, Press Conference, Pennsylvania Treasurer's Office|date = January 22, 1987|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Dwyer|first = R. Budd}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> The timing of Dwyer's press conference and suicide meant that Thornburgh was not empowered to appoint a Treasurer to replace him. Instead, this fell to Thornburgh's successor, Democrat Bob Casey, who had taken office on January 20.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Casey Vows Political Open Door 5,000 View Inaugural Ceremony|url = http://articles.philly.com/1987-01-21/news/26191261_1_robert-p-casey-ceremonies-new-governor|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe letter Dwyer had sent to Casey stated, among other things, \"By the time you receive this letter ... the office of State Treasurer of Pennsylvania will be vacant. I stress to you that I did not resign but was State Treasurer of Pennsylvania to the end.\" It also stated that Casey \"will be the great Governor that Pennsylvania needs at this time in our history.\" He suggested his wife Joanne as his successor, describing her as \"very talented, personable, organized and hard-working.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title = OFFICIAL CALLS IN PRESS AND KILLS HIMSELF|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/23/us/official-calls-in-press-and-kills-himself.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = January 23, 1987|access-date = November 8, 2015|issn = 0362-4331|first = William K. Stevens, Special To The New York|last = Times}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Casey did not take Dwyer's suggestion. Regardless of the events of January 22, the governor and legislature of Pennsylvania already expected Dwyer to either resign or be removed from office. As such, a deal had already been brokered wherein the next treasurer, a Democrat, would serve out Dwyer's term and step down at its end. This was [[G. Davis Greene Jr.]], who was appointed as the 31st Treasurer of Pennsylvania on January 23, 1987, the day after Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|title = G. Davis Greene Jr., 81, former state treasurer|url = http://articles.philly.com/2012-09-06/news/33617725_1_financial-adviser-state-treasurer-bob-casey|website = philly-archives|accessdate = November 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Response to allegations made by Dwyer in his final press statement===\nFollowing Dwyer's public suicide, the [[National Association of State Treasurers]] called for Dwyer's allegations (contained in his final press statement) to be reviewed by the [[United States Department of Justice]]. After a thorough investigation, the Justice Department's [[Office of Professional Responsibility]] cleared attorney James West and everyone else involved in Dwyer's investigation and prosecution, of any wrongdoing. The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] also investigated Dwyer's claims regarding impropriety on behalf of FBI personnel. They ultimately found Dwyer's claims to be \"lacking in substance and specificity\" and warranting no further action.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/BuddDwyer Budd Dwyer : Federal Bureau of Investigation : Free Download, Borrow, and Streaming : Internet Archive<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Death benefits===\nSince Dwyer died in office, his widow Joanne was able to collect full survivor benefits totaling over $1.28 million, which at the time was the largest death benefit payment ever made by the state system. If Dwyer had been sentenced, state law would have prohibited the payment of his state-provided pension benefits.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" /><ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=April 16, 1987 |title=Family to Get $1.28-Million Pension in Suicide of Pennsylvania Official |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-751_1_pension-benefit |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025022622/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-751_1_pension-benefit |archive-date=October 25, 2015}}</ref> A spokesman for Dwyer suggested that he may have killed himself to preserve the pension benefits for his family, whose finances had been ruined by legal defense costs.<ref>\"Pennsylvania Official's Suicide May Be Linked to Finances\", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', January 24, 1987.</ref> Other statements made by friends and family also suggest that this was Dwyer's motivation.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n\n==Appeals==\nOn January 27, 1987, Dwyer's lawyers filed an appeal in the [[U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Pennsylvania]] seeking the dismissal of all post-trial motions that were then pending against Dwyer, abatement of Dwyer's conviction and the dismissal of his May 13, 1986 indictment. On March 5, 1987, the district court denied all motions, and ordered to \"close this file as to R. Budd Dwyer.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/654/1254/1690114/|title=United States v. Dwyer, 654 F. Supp. 1254 (M.D. Pa. 1987)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Dwyer's lawyers appealed this decision, and [[The US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] subsequently vacated the judgement. On remand, the district court was instructed to dismiss Dwyer's motions (since the Court lacked subject matter jurisdiction) and Dwyer's convictions for mail fraud and conspiracy were upheld. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/855/144/372541/|title=United States of America v. Dwyer, R. Budd, Appellant, 855 F.2d 144 (3d Cir. 1988)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Six years after Dwyer's death, efforts were made to clear Dwyer's name when a retrial request was filed in U.S. District Court in July 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/6cffa3fdd182b37efd86fa3b18677837|title=Six Years After Suicide, New Trial Sought To Clear Budd Dwyer|date=July 26, 1993|website=AP News|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> This request was denied in October of the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42459010/judge_turns_down_motion_for_dwyer/|title=Judge turns down motion for Dwyer retrial|date=October 28, 1993|work=Indiana Gazette|access-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Associate Press}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*The 1988 [[Rapeman]] EP ''[[Budd (EP)|Budd]]'' is named after Dwyer, and its first track, which shares the EP's name, contains lyrics referencing his suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.touchandgorecords.com/bands/band.php?id=63|title=Rapeman: Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records|accessdate=June 8, 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Faith No More]]'s 1992 ''[[Angel Dust (Faith No More album)|Angel Dust]]'' b-side \"The World Is Yours\" samples audio of Dwyer's suicide.\n*[[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]]'s debut single \"[[Get Your Gunn]]\" (1994) samples audio of Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/marilyn-manson-i-like-to-smoke-and-hang-out-with-the-gangsta-rappers-6615701|title=Marilyn Manson: \"I Like To Smoke and Hang Out With The Gangsta Rappers\"|last=Louvau|first=Jim|date=May 30, 2013|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 1995 song \"[[Hey Man Nice Shot]]\" by the band [[Filter (band)|Filter]] is about Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://klaq.com/richard-patrick-of-filter-talks-about-hey-man-nice-shot-and-kurt-cobain/|title=Richard Patrick of Filter Talks About 'Hey Man Nice Shot' and Kurt Cobain|work=[[KLAQ]]|last=Adams|first=Buzz|date=June 29, 2012|accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n*The 1999 album ''[[Volume 1 (CKY album)|Volume 1]]'' by Pennsylvania [[alternative rock]] band [[CKY (band)|CKY]] initially featured an artistic depiction of Dwyer committing suicide. When the band later signed with [[Volcom]], the album art was changed as the label found the graphic to be too offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/future-shock-she-wants-revenge-the-donnas-cky-and-more-6595143|title=Future Shock: She Wants Revenge, The Donnas, CKY, and more|last=D'Andrea|first=Nika|date=August 17, 2007|website=[[Phoenix New Times]]|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}<</ref>\n*The 2002 documentary film ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'' includes footage of Dwyer's suicide as part of a montage of gun-related video clips.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/bowling-for-columbine/oclc/224200985?referer=di&ht=edition|title=Bowling for Columbine|date=2002|oclc=224200985|quote=Abstract:...Footage of and interviews with: ...R. Budd Dwyer (handgun suicide whose death was televised in the U.S.)...|medium=film}}</ref>\n* In 2003, the band [[Ion Dissonance]] featured a song called \"The Bud Dwyer Effect\" on their album ''[[Breathing Is Irrelevant]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathing-is-irrelevant-mw0000317092|title=Breathing Is Irrelevant - Ion Dissonance|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2006 film ''[[Loren Cass]]'' shows footage of Dwyer's suicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Loren Cass|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/loren-cass-1200558580/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Koehler|first=Robert|date=June 13, 2007|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*The 2010 documentary ''[[Honest Man: The Life of R. Budd Dwyer]]'' by director James Dirschberger detailed the events of the CTA scandal that led to Dwyer's suicide.<ref name=\"Honest Man\" />\n* On their 2013 album ''Hellbound'', New Jersey [[Deathcore]] band [[Fit for an Autopsy]] paid homage to Dwyer in their song \"Thank You, Budd Dwyer\". The band stated that the song was in response to the injustices in the legal system and maintained that Dwyer was a victim of wrongful accusations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fit For An Autopsy Thank Budd Dwyer|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2013/09/04/fit-for-an-autopsy-thank-budd-dwyer/|website=[[MetalSucks]]|last=Rosenberg|first=Axl|date=September 4, 2013|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*The cover art for [[Suicideboys]]' 2017 EP, ''Kill Yourself Part III: The Budd Dwyer Saga'', features a still frame of Dwyer with the gun in his mouth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.napster.com/artist/suicideboys/album/kill-yourself-part-iii-the-budd-dwyer-saga|title=Kill Yourself Part III: The Budd Dwyer Saga|website=Napster|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Grossman|first=Mark|title=Political corruption in America: an encyclopedia of scandals, power, and greed|url=https://archive.org/details/politicalcorrupt0000gros/page/108|url-access=registration|edition=2003|pages=108|year=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-060-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Keisling|first=William|title=The Sins of Our Fathers|edition=2011|year=2003|publisher=Yardbird Books|isbn=978-0-9620251-0-5}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Yuhasz |first1=Lorraine |title=The Dwyer Case |date=1998 |publisher=Friends of Dwyer Committee |isbn=978-1882611140 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6129|R. Budd Dwyer}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert E. Casey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Pennsylvania Treasurer|Treasurer of Pennsylvania]]|years=1981\u20131987}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[G. Davis Greene, Jr.]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dwyer, Budd}}\n[[Category:R. Budd Dwyer| ]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Allegheny College alumni]]\n[[Category:American politicians who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Educators from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Filmed suicides]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pennsylvania House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania state senators]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Meadville, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from St. Charles, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of corruption in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of mail and wire fraud]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of racketeering]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Organ transplant donors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:Educators from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Sam Golden", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBribery investigation and convicti